    "FamilyDetail.ierenLong" : {
      "localizations" : {
        "en" : {
          "stringUnit" : {
            "state" : "translated",
            "value" : "~-Ieren~ verbs came to German through Latin and French. Latin verbs in ~-are~ (like ~studiare~, to study) became French verbs in ~-er~, which German then borrowed with the characteristic ~-ieren~ ending.\n\nThese verbs behave like weak verbs with one key exception: they form the ~Perfektpartizip~ without the ~ge-~ prefix. So ~studieren~ becomes ~studiert~ (not ~gestudiert~), and ~telefonieren~ becomes ~telefoniert~.\n\nMany -ieren verbs describe modern concepts or formal activities: ~telefonieren~ (telephone), ~organisieren~ (organize), ~funktionieren~ (function), ~diskutieren~ (discuss). Their Latin-French origin often makes them recognizable to English speakers."
          }
        }
      }
    },
    "FamilyDetail.inseparableLong" : {
      "localizations" : {
        "en" : {
          "stringUnit" : {
            "state" : "translated",
            "value" : "~Inseparable-prefix~ verbs have prefixes that never detach from the verb stem. English equivalents include \"unfriend\" (un- never separates) or \"overcome\" (over- stays attached).\n\nThe eight inseparable prefixes are ~be-~, ~emp-~, ~ent-~, ~er-~, ~ge-~, ~miss-~, ~ver-~, and ~zer-~. Each carries a distinct meaning that modifies the base verb. For example, ~ver-~ often indicates completion or error: ~stehen~ (stand) â†’ ~verstehen~ (understand).\n\nInseparable verbs form the ~Perfektpartizip~ without adding ~ge-~, since the prefix occupies that position. So ~verstehen~ becomes ~verstanden~, not ~geverstanden~.\n\nIn the table that follows, ğŸ´ó §ó ¢ó ¥ó ®ó §ó ¿ precedes the English meaning of a German prefix; ğŸ precedes the Proto-Indo-European root of that prefix and the root's meaning; and * precedes the scholarly reconstruction."
          }
        }
      }
    },
    "FamilyDetail.mixedLong" : {
      "localizations" : {
        "en" : {
          "stringUnit" : {
            "state" : "translated",
            "value" : "~Mixed~ verbs combine features of both strong and weak verbs. Like strong verbs, they undergo a vowel change (ablaut) in the past tense. But like weak verbs, they use the ~-te~ suffix for the ~PrÃ¤teritum~ and ~-t~ for the ~Perfektpartizip~.\n\nThe most common mixed verbs include ~bringen~ (bring, $brAchte$, $gebrAcht$), ~denken~ (think, $dAchte$, $gedAcht$), ~kennen~ (know, $kAnnte$, $gekAnnt$), and ~wissen~ (know facts, $wUsste$, $gewUsst$).\n\nMixed verbs likely arose when some strong verbs began following the more productive weak pattern while retaining their vowel changes. This hybrid category is small but includes several high-frequency verbs essential for everyday German."
          }
        }
      }
    },
    "FamilyDetail.prefixesHeading" : {
      "localizations" : {
        "en" : {
          "stringUnit" : {
            "state" : "translated",
            "value" : "Prefixes"
          }
        }
