    },
    "FamilyDetail.separableLong" : {
      "localizations" : {
        "en" : {
          "stringUnit" : {
            "state" : "translated",
            "value" : "~Separable-prefix~ verbs have prefixes that detach from the verb in main clauses and move to the end of the sentence. English phrasal verbs work similarly: \"pick up\" â†’ \"I pick the phone up\" or \"come in\" â†’ \"Please come in\".\n\nIn German: ~ankommen~ (arrive) â†’ ~Ich komme morgen an~ (I arrive tomorrow). The prefix ~an-~ moves to the end. In subordinate clauses, the prefix stays attached: ~...weil ich morgen ankomme~.\n\nSeparable verbs form the ~Perfektpartizip~ by inserting ~ge-~ between the prefix and stem: ~ankommen~ â†’ ~angekommen~. This mirrors how the prefix separates in speech.\n\nIn the table that follows, ğŸ´ó §ó ¢ó ¥ó ®ó §ó ¿ precedes the English meaning of a German prefix; ğŸ precedes the Proto-Indo-European root of that prefix and the root's meaning; and * precedes the scholarly reconstruction."
          }
        }
      }
    },
    "FamilyDetail.strongLong" : {
      "localizations" : {
        "en" : {
          "stringUnit" : {
            "state" : "translated",
            "value" : "~Strong~ verbs are the oldest verb pattern in German, inherited from Proto-Indo-European. They signal tense through vowel changes called ~ablaut~ rather than by adding suffixes. English retains this pattern in verbs like ~sing~, $sAng$, $sUng$ or ~drive~, $drOve$, $drIven$.\n\nThe ~Perfektpartizip~ of strong verbs ends in ~-en~ (like ~gesungen~, ~gefahren~) rather than the ~-t~ of weak verbs. This ~-en~ ending is another ancient feature shared with English (sung, driven).\n\nGerman has about 170 strong verbs, but they include many of the most common verbs in the language: ~sein~ (be), ~haben~ (have), ~gehen~ (go), ~kommen~ (come), ~sehen~ (see), ~geben~ (give). Despite being \"irregular\", strong verbs follow predictable ablaut patterns grouped by vowel series."
          }
        }
      }
    },
    "FamilyDetail.verbsHeading" : {
      "localizations" : {
        "en" : {
