        "en" : {
          "stringUnit" : {
            "state" : "translated",
            "value" : "`About`The ~Futur Indikativ~â€”often called simply ~Futur I~â€”is German's primary way of expressing future actions using a dedicated grammatical construction. It combines the auxiliary verb ~werden~ with the infinitive of the main verb: \"Ich ~werde~ morgen ~kommen~\" (I will come tomorrow).\n\nThis compound conjugationgroup serves several functions:\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~Future actions~: Expressing what will happen. \"Er ~wird~ das Buch ~lesen~.\" = \"He will read the book.\"\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~Intentions and plans~: Stating what one intends to do. \"Ich ~werde~ dich morgen ~anrufen~.\" = \"I will call you tomorrow.\"\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~Predictions~: Forecasting likely outcomes. \"Es ~wird~ regnen.\" = \"It will rain.\"\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~Promises and resolutions~: Committing to future action. \"Ich ~werde~ es nie ~vergessen~.\" = \"I will never forget it.\"\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~Present probability~: Expressing what is probably true now. \"Er ~wird~ wohl krank ~sein~.\" = \"He is probably sick.\"\n\nInterestingly, German often uses the PrÃ¤sens with a time adverb to express future meaning: \"Ich ~komme~ morgen\" (I'm coming tomorrow). The Futur Indikativ is not strictly required for future referenceâ€”but it adds emphasis, formality, or certainty to future statements.`Formation`The Futur Indikativ has a simple structure: conjugate ~werden~ for the subject, then add the infinitive of the main verb at the end of the clause.`Conjugation of werden`The auxiliary ~werden~ conjugates irregularly in the present:\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ich ~werde~ (I will)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª du ~wirst~ (you will)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª er/sie/es ~wird~ (he/she/it will)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª wir ~werden~ (we will)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ihr ~werdet~ (you all will)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª sie/Sie ~werden~ (they/you formal will)\n\nNote the stem change in 2s and 3s: ~wirst~, ~wird~.`Complete Examples`\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª Ich ~werde~ das Buch ~lesen~. (I will read the book.)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª Du ~wirst~ es ~verstehen~. (You will understand it.)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª Er ~wird~ nach Berlin ~fahren~. (He will go to Berlin.)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª Wir ~werden~ frÃ¼h ~aufstehen~. (We will get up early.)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª Ihr ~werdet~ es ~sehen~. (You all will see it.)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª Sie ~werden~ bald ~ankommen~. (They will arrive soon.)`Word Order`In main clauses, ~werden~ takes the second position (V2), while the infinitive moves to the end:\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª \"Ich ~werde~ morgen das Buch ~lesen~.\" = \"I will read the book tomorrow.\"\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª \"Sie ~wird~ nÃ¤chste Woche nach Paris ~fliegen~.\" = \"She will fly to Paris next week.\"\n\nIn subordinate clauses, both elements move to the end, with the infinitive preceding ~werden~:\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª \"Ich weiÃŸ, dass er das Buch ~lesen wird~.\" = \"I know that he will read the book.\"\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª \"Weil sie ~kommen wird~, bereite ich das Essen vor.\" = \"Because she will come, I'm preparing the food.\"\n\nThis bracket structure (~Verbklammer~) parallels other compound tenses.`Futur by Verb Family`The infinitive remains unchanged regardless of verb familyâ€”all complexity is handled by ~werden~.`Weak Verbs`\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª machen â†’ ich ~werde~ ~machen~ (I will make)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª sagen â†’ er ~wird~ ~sagen~ (he will say)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª arbeiten â†’ wir ~werden~ ~arbeiten~ (we will work)`Strong Verbs`\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª sehen â†’ ich ~werde~ ~sehen~ (I will see)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª gehen â†’ du ~wirst~ ~gehen~ (you will go)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª kommen â†’ sie ~wird~ ~kommen~ (she will come)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª nehmen â†’ wir ~werden~ ~nehmen~ (we will take)`Mixed Verbs`\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª bringen â†’ ich ~werde~ ~bringen~ (I will bring)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª denken â†’ er ~wird~ ~denken~ (he will think)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª wissen â†’ sie ~werden~ ~wissen~ (they will know)`-Ieren Verbs`\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª studieren â†’ ich ~werde~ ~studieren~ (I will study)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª telefonieren â†’ er ~wird~ ~telefonieren~ (he will call)`Separable-Prefix Verbs`Separable prefixes remain attached to the infinitive:\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ankommen â†’ ich ~werde~ ~ankommen~ (I will arrive)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª aufstehen â†’ du ~wirst~ ~aufstehen~ (you will get up)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª mitnehmen â†’ er ~wird~ ~mitnehmen~ (he will take along)`Modal Verbs`Modal verbs also form the Futur with ~werden~:\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª kÃ¶nnen â†’ ich ~werde~ ~kÃ¶nnen~ (I will be able to)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª mÃ¼ssen â†’ er ~wird~ ~mÃ¼ssen~ (he will have to)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª wollen â†’ sie ~wird~ ~wollen~ (she will want to)\n\nThese double-infinitive constructions are grammatically correct but often sound awkward; speakers frequently prefer the present tense with modal verbs.`Futur vs. PrÃ¤sens for Future Meaning`German often uses the ~PrÃ¤sens~ with a time adverb to express future meaning:\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª \"Ich ~komme~ morgen.\" = \"I'm coming tomorrow.\" / \"I'll come tomorrow.\"\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª \"NÃ¤chstes Jahr ~fahren~ wir nach Italien.\" = \"Next year we'll go to Italy.\"\n\nThis is fully grammatical and extremely commonâ€”especially in casual speech. So when is the Futur Indikativ preferred?\n\n~Use Futur Indikativ for~:\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~Emphasis or determination~: \"Ich ~werde~ es schaffen!\" (I WILL succeed!)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~Formal contexts~: Announcements, promises, official statements.\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~Predictions without time adverb~: \"Es ~wird~ regnen.\" (It will rain.)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~Present probability~: \"Er ~wird~ wohl zu Hause sein.\" (He's probably at home.)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~Distant future~: When the time frame is unspecified or remote.\n\n~Use PrÃ¤sens for~:\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~Immediate or scheduled future~: \"Der Zug ~fÃ¤hrt~ um 10 Uhr.\" (The train leaves at 10.)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~Casual conversation~: \"Ich ~gehe~ spÃ¤ter einkaufen.\" (I'm going shopping later.)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~Clear time context~: When an adverb like ~morgen~, ~bald~, ~nÃ¤chste Woche~ makes the future reference obvious.`The Probability Meaning`A distinctive feature of German's Futur Indikativ is its use for ~present probability~â€”expressing what is likely true now, not what will happen:\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª \"Er ~wird~ wohl krank ~sein~.\" = \"He is probably sick.\" (not: \"He will be sick.\")\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª \"Sie ~wird~ das schon ~wissen~.\" = \"She probably knows that already.\"\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª \"Das ~wird~ stimmen.\" = \"That's probably true.\"\n\nParticles like ~wohl~, ~schon~, and ~wohl schon~ often accompany this usage. Context distinguishes probability from true future: \"Er ~wird kommen~\" means \"He will come,\" but \"Er ~wird wohl kommen~\" leans toward \"He's probably coming\" (or \"He'll probably come\").`Differences from English`German and English future expressions differ in several ways:\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~Single auxiliary~: German uses only ~werden~ for the future; English distinguishes \"will\" (prediction/volition) from \"shall\" (determination/suggestion in formal British), \"going to\" (intention/imminent), and present progressive (\"I'm leaving tomorrow\").\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~PrÃ¤sens as future~: German uses the present tense for future meaning far more readily than standard English. \"Ich komme morgen\" is fully natural; English \"I come tomorrow\" sounds marked or literary.\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~Probability function~: German ~werden~ + infinitive can express present probabilityâ€”a meaning English \"will\" rarely conveys. English requires separate constructions (\"He must be sick,\" \"He's probably sick\").\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~Emphasis~: German Futur often adds emphasis or determination that the PrÃ¤sens lacks. \"Ich werde es tun\" is more forceful than \"Ich tue es.\"`Historical Development`The Futur Indikativ with ~werden~ is a relatively recent development in the history of German. Old High German (c. 750â€“1050) had no dedicated future tense; speakers used the present tense with context or adverbs to indicate futurityâ€”a pattern that continues today.\n\nThe verb ~werden~ originally meant \"to become\" (as it still does: \"Er ~wird~ Arzt\" = \"He is becoming a doctor\"). During the Middle High German period (c. 1050â€“1350), ~werden~ + infinitive began grammaticalizing into a future construction, probably influenced by Latin and French models that had dedicated future conjugations.\n\nBy Early New High German (c. 1350â€“1650), the ~werden~-future was established, though the present tense remained (and remains) a viable alternative. Martin Luther's Bible translation (1534) uses both constructions freely, showing the coexistence that persists in modern German.\n\nThe \"becoming\" meaning of ~werden~ is still faintly visible in the future: \"Ich werde kommen\" contains an echo of \"I am becoming [one who] comes\"â€”a dynamic becoming that evolves toward the future action.`Literary Examples`The Futur Indikativ appears in German literature for predictions, promises, and emphatic declarations.`Goethe â€” The Sorrows of Young Werther (1774)`\"Ich ~werde~ ihn ehster Tage ~besuchen~.\" = \"I shall visit him very soon.\"\n\nWerther states his intention formally, using the Futur to signal a definite plan. The ~werde besuchen~ construction gives more weight than a simple present would.\n\n\"Bald ~werde~ ich Herr vom Garten ~sein~.\" = \"Soon I shall be master of the place.\"\n\nWerther's anticipation of tending a garden uses the Futur to project forward to a desired stateâ€”a small happiness he envisions amid his turmoil.\n\n\"Ich ~werde~ mich kÃ¼nftig allein an die Natur ~halten~.\" = \"I will adhere only to nature henceforth.\"\n\nThis resolutionâ€”a turning away from artistic rules toward natural feelingâ€”uses the Futur to mark a decisive change in Werther's approach.`Kafka â€” The Trial (1925)`\"Sie ~werden~ alles zur richtigen Zeit ~erfahren~.\" = \"You'll learn about everything all in good time.\"\n\nThe court official's dismissive response to K.'s questions uses the Futur with bureaucratic vagueness. The ~werden erfahren~ promises future knowledge while revealing nothing present.\n\n\"Ich ~werde~ bald ~weggehen~.\" = \"I'll soon be leaving.\"\n\nSimple Futur for a straightforward departureâ€”K. announces his imminent exit from a scene that has become uncomfortable.`Mann â€” Death in Venice (1912)`\"Er ~wird~ nicht alt ~werden~.\" = \"In all probability he will not grow old.\"\n\nAschenbach's observation about Tadzio uses the Futur for a grim prediction. The ~wird werden~ construction (auxiliary ~wird~ + infinitive ~werden~) is grammatically unremarkable but semantically poignantâ€”the beautiful boy's death is foreseen.\n\nNote the probability nuance here: \"wird nicht alt werden\" could mean \"he will not grow old\" (prediction) or \"he is probably not going to grow old\" (inference). Context suggests Aschenbach is inferring from Tadzio's frail constitution.`Why the Futur Indikativ Matters`The Futur Indikativ is essential for:\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~Formal announcements~: \"Die Sitzung ~wird~ um 14 Uhr ~beginnen~.\"\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~Promises and commitments~: \"Ich ~werde~ es nie ~vergessen~.\"\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~Emphatic declarations~: \"Das ~werde~ ich ~tun~!\"\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~Expressing probability~: \"Sie ~wird~ wohl schon ~wissen~.\"\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~Written and formal German~: Where the PrÃ¤sens might seem too casual.\n\nMastering the Futur Indikativ means understanding not just how to conjugate it, but ~when~ to use itâ€”knowing that the PrÃ¤sens with a time adverb is often sufficient for casual future reference, while the ~werden~-construction adds emphasis, formality, or probability. This pragmatic awareness distinguishes fluent German usage from merely correct grammar."
