            "value" : "`About`The ~Futur Konjunktiv II~â€”conjugated with ~wÃ¼rde~ + infinitiveâ€”is German's most versatile conditional construction. It expresses hypothetical, counterfactual, and politely uncertain future actions: what ~would~ happen, what one ~would~ do, what ~would~ be the case if circumstances were different.\n\nThis compound conjugationgroup combines:\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª The auxiliary verb ~wÃ¼rde~ (PrÃ¤teritum Konjunktiv II of ~werden~)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª The ~infinitive~ of the main verb\n\nThe result: \"Ich ~wÃ¼rde~ gern ~helfen~\" (I would gladly help) or \"Er ~wÃ¼rde~ kommen, wenn er kÃ¶nnte\" (He would come if he could).\n\nThe ~wÃ¼rde~-construction has become the dominant way to express conditionality in modern German, especially in speech. While strong verbs retain their synthetic PrÃ¤teritum Konjunktiv II conjugations (~kÃ¤me~, ~gÃ¤be~, ~sÃ¤he~), weak verbs and many strong verbs now prefer the ~wÃ¼rde~ + infinitive construction for clarity and ease.`Conjugation`The Futur Konjunktiv II uses ~wÃ¼rde~ (the Konjunktiv II conjugation of ~werden~) plus the infinitive of the main verb.`Conjugation of wÃ¼rde`\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ich ~wÃ¼rde~ (I would)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª du ~wÃ¼rdest~ (you would)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª er/sie/es ~wÃ¼rde~ (he/she/it would)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª wir ~wÃ¼rden~ (we would)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ihr ~wÃ¼rdet~ (you all would)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª sie/Sie ~wÃ¼rden~ (they/you formal would)\n\nThese conjugations derive from ~werden~ via the standard Konjunktiv II pattern: PrÃ¤teritum stem (~wurd-~) + umlaut (~wÃ¼rd-~) + subjunctive endings.`Complete Examples`\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª Ich ~wÃ¼rde~ das Buch ~lesen~. (I would read the book.)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª Du ~wÃ¼rdest~ es ~verstehen~. (You would understand it.)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª Er ~wÃ¼rde~ gern ~helfen~. (He would gladly help.)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª Wir ~wÃ¼rden~ nach Berlin ~fahren~. (We would go to Berlin.)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª Ihr ~wÃ¼rdet~ es ~sehen~. (You all would see it.)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª Sie ~wÃ¼rden~ zustimmen. (They would agree.)`Word Order`In main clauses, ~wÃ¼rde~ takes the second position (V2), while the infinitive moves to the end:\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª \"Ich ~wÃ¼rde~ gern morgen ~kommen~.\" = \"I would gladly come tomorrow.\"\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª \"Sie ~wÃ¼rde~ das nie ~sagen~.\" = \"She would never say that.\"\n\nIn subordinate clauses, both elements move to the end, with the infinitive preceding ~wÃ¼rde~:\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª \"Ich weiÃŸ, dass er es ~tun wÃ¼rde~.\" = \"I know that he would do it.\"\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª \"Wenn sie ~kommen wÃ¼rde~, wÃ¤re ich froh.\" = \"If she would come, I would be happy.\"`Futur Konjunktiv II by Verb Family`The infinitive remains unchanged regardless of verb familyâ€”all the conditional meaning is carried by ~wÃ¼rde~.`Weak Verbs`\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª machen â†’ ich ~wÃ¼rde~ ~machen~ (I would make)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª sagen â†’ er ~wÃ¼rde~ ~sagen~ (he would say)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª arbeiten â†’ wir ~wÃ¼rden~ ~arbeiten~ (we would work)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª kaufen â†’ sie ~wÃ¼rden~ ~kaufen~ (they would buy)\n\nFor weak verbs, the ~wÃ¼rde~-construction is strongly preferred because their synthetic Konjunktiv II conjugations are identical to the PrÃ¤teritum Indikativ (~machte~, ~sagte~), creating ambiguity.`Strong Verbs`\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª sehen â†’ ich ~wÃ¼rde~ ~sehen~ (I would see)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª gehen â†’ du ~wÃ¼rdest~ ~gehen~ (you would go)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª kommen â†’ er ~wÃ¼rde~ ~kommen~ (he would come)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª nehmen â†’ wir ~wÃ¼rden~ ~nehmen~ (we would take)\n\nStrong verbs have distinct synthetic Konjunktiv II conjugations (~sÃ¤he~, ~ginge~, ~kÃ¤me~, ~nÃ¤hme~), but the ~wÃ¼rde~-construction is increasingly common in colloquial German.`Separable-Prefix Verbs`Separable prefixes remain attached to the infinitive:\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ankommen â†’ ich ~wÃ¼rde~ ~ankommen~ (I would arrive)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª aufstehen â†’ du ~wÃ¼rdest~ ~aufstehen~ (you would get up)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª mitnehmen â†’ er ~wÃ¼rde~ ~mitnehmen~ (he would take along)`wÃ¼rde vs. Synthetic Konjunktiv II Conjugations`German has two ways to express conditionality: the synthetic conjugations (PrÃ¤teritum Konjunktiv II) and the analytic ~wÃ¼rde~-construction. How do they differ?\n\n~Synthetic conjugations~ (kÃ¤me, gÃ¤be, sÃ¤he, etc.):\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª More formal and literary\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª Preferred for high-frequency verbs: ~wÃ¤re~, ~hÃ¤tte~, ~kÃ¶nnte~, ~mÃ¼sste~, ~sollte~, ~wollte~\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª Common in southern German dialects\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª Required for ~sein~, ~haben~, and modal verbs in careful usage\n\n~wÃ¼rde + infinitive~:\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª More colloquial and widespread\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª Strongly preferred for weak verbs (avoids PrÃ¤teritum/Konjunktiv II ambiguity)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª Increasingly common even for strong verbs in speech\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª Universal fallback when synthetic conjugation is unknown or awkward\n\nIn practice, both constructions coexist. A sentence like \"Wenn ich reich ~wÃ¤re~, ~wÃ¼rde~ ich ein Haus ~kaufen~\" uses the synthetic ~wÃ¤re~ for ~sein~ but the analytic ~wÃ¼rde kaufen~ for ~kaufen~â€”a natural mixing of conjugations.`Usage Contexts``Hypothetical Conditions`The Futur Konjunktiv II appears in the main clause of unreal conditional sentences:\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª \"Wenn ich Zeit hÃ¤tte, ~wÃ¼rde~ ich dir ~helfen~.\" = \"If I had time, I would help you.\"\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª \"Wenn es nicht regnete, ~wÃ¼rden~ wir spazieren ~gehen~.\" = \"If it weren't raining, we would go for a walk.\"\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª \"~WÃ¼rdest~ du ~kommen~, wenn ich dich einlade?\" = \"Would you come if I invited you?\"`Polite Requests and Suggestions`The ~wÃ¼rde~-construction softens requests:\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª \"~WÃ¼rden~ Sie mir bitte ~helfen~?\" = \"Would you please help me?\"\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª \"Ich ~wÃ¼rde~ vorschlagen, dass wir frÃ¼her anfangen.\" = \"I would suggest that we start earlier.\"\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª \"~WÃ¼rdest~ du das Fenster ~Ã¶ffnen~?\" = \"Would you open the window?\"`Wishes and Desires`Expressing what one would like:\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª \"Ich ~wÃ¼rde~ gern nach Japan ~reisen~.\" = \"I would like to travel to Japan.\"\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª \"Er ~wÃ¼rde~ lieber zu Hause ~bleiben~.\" = \"He would rather stay home.\"\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª \"Wir ~wÃ¼rden~ uns freuen, Sie wiederzusehen.\" = \"We would be pleased to see you again.\"`Reported Conditional`Expressing what someone would do according to report:\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª \"Er sagte, er ~wÃ¼rde~ uns ~helfen~.\" = \"He said he would help us.\"\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª \"Sie meinte, sie ~wÃ¼rde~ spÃ¤ter ~anrufen~.\" = \"She said she would call later.\"` Differences from English`The German ~wÃ¼rde~-construction parallels English \"would\" closely, but some differences exist:\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~Competition with synthetic conjugations~: German retains synthetic Konjunktiv II conjugations (~kÃ¤me~, ~wÃ¤re~) that compete with the analytic construction. English \"would\" has no such competitor for most verbs.\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~Weak verb preference~: German strongly prefers ~wÃ¼rde~ for weak verbs because their synthetic conjugations are ambiguous. English has no parallel concern.\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~Auxiliary exceptions~: German still strongly prefers ~wÃ¤re~, ~hÃ¤tte~, and modal Konjunktiv II conjugations over ~wÃ¼rde sein~, ~wÃ¼rde haben~, etc. English uses \"would be,\" \"would have\" freely.\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~Politeness marking~: German ~wÃ¼rde~ conjugations are more explicitly marked as polite/conditional than English \"would,\" which has broader uses (habitual past: \"He would always arrive late\").`Historical Development`The ~wÃ¼rde~-construction emerged in Middle High German (c. 1050â€“1350) as an alternative to synthetic subjunctive conjugations. The verb ~werden~ had long meant \"to become,\" and its subjunctive (~wÃ¼rde~) began combining with infinitives to express futurity and conditionality.\n\nBy Early New High German (c. 1350â€“1650), the construction was well established, especially for weak verbs whose synthetic Konjunktiv II conjugations had merged with the PrÃ¤teritum Indikativ. The pattern ~ich wÃ¼rde machen~ provided an unambiguous conditional alternative to ~ich machte~ (which could mean \"I made\" or \"I would make\").\n\nOver the following centuries, the ~wÃ¼rde~-construction expanded steadily, displacing synthetic conjugations even for many strong verbs in colloquial speech. Today, it serves as the default conditional for all but the most common verbsâ€”a grammaticalization process that transformed \"would become\" into a pure conditional marker.`Literary Examples`The Futur Konjunktiv II appears throughout German literature for hypothetical reasoning, polite suggestion, and contrary-to-fact imagination.`Goethe â€” The Sorrows of Young Werther (1774)`\"Ich ~wÃ¼rde~ sagen: du bist ein Tor! Du suchst, was hienieden nicht zu finden ist!\" = \"I would say: you are a fool! You seek what is not to be found here below!\"\n\nWerther imagines what he ~would~ say to himselfâ€”a self-critical hypothetical. The ~wÃ¼rde sagen~ frames the accusation as a judgment he might pass, not one he fully accepts.\n\n\"HÃ¤tte er gewartet, bis seine KrÃ¤fte sich erholt, alles ~wÃ¤re~ gut ~gegangen~.\" = \"Had he waited until his strength was restored, all ~would~ have ~gone~ well.\"\n\nAlbert's argument about suicide uses the Konjunktiv II (~wÃ¤re gegangen~) to express a counterfactual outcomeâ€”what ~would~ have happened if the patient had acted differently. Here the synthetic conjugation appears rather than ~wÃ¼rde~.`Kafka â€” The Trial (1925)`\"~WÃ¼rde~ man ihm nicht glauben, so konnte er Frau Grubach als Zeugin fÃ¼hren.\" = \"Should they not believe him, he could call Mrs. Grubach as a witness.\"\n\nK.'s contingency planning uses ~wÃ¼rde~ to set up a hypothetical scenario: if they ~would~ not believe him, then a backup plan exists.\n\n\"Wollte er einen andern Termin wÃ¼nschen, so ~wÃ¼rde~ man ihm, so gut es ginge, ~entgegenkommen~.\" = \"Should he wish a different time, they ~would~ accommodate him as best they could.\"\n\nThe court's message uses ~wÃ¼rde entgegenkommen~ to express conditional willingnessâ€”a promise contingent on K.'s wishes.`Mann â€” Death in Venice (1912)`\"HÃ¤tte er sie ein wenig zurÃ¼ckbehalten, hÃ¤tte er es auf den Versuch einer Anpassung ankommen lassen, so ~wÃ¼rde~ ihm ein Vormittag am Strande ~bevorstehen~.\" = \"Had he held back a bit, had he allowed himself to try adapting, a morning on the beach ~would~ await him.\"\n\nMann's elaborate counterfactual uses ~wÃ¼rde bevorstehen~ in the main clauseâ€”what ~would~ have been the result of a different choice. The contrary-to-fact condition imagines an alternative to Aschenbach's departure from Venice.`Why the Futur Konjunktiv II Matters`The Futur Konjunktiv II is essential for:\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~Everyday politeness~: \"~WÃ¼rden~ Sie mir bitte helfen?\" is standard polite German.\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~Hypothetical discussion~: Debating what ~would~ happen, what one ~would~ do.\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~Weak verb conditionality~: The ~wÃ¼rde~-construction provides unambiguous conditional meaning where synthetic conjugations are ambiguous.\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~Universal fallback~: When you don't know or can't recall a synthetic Konjunktiv II conjugation, ~wÃ¼rde~ + infinitive is always correct.\n\nMastering the Futur Konjunkti II means mastering the most productive conditional pattern in modern German. While purists may prefer ~kÃ¤me~ to ~wÃ¼rde kommen~, the analytic construction is grammatically impeccable and universally understood. It is the Swiss Army knife of German conditionalityâ€”always available, always clear, always correct."
