            "value" : "`About`The ~Futur Konjunktiv I~ is German's conjugationgroup for reporting future events in indirect speech. While the PrÃ¤sens Konjunktiv I reports what someone says is happening now, and the Perfekt Konjunktiv I reports what someone said happened, the Futur Konjunktiv I reports what someone says ~will happen~â€”future events viewed through the lens of reported speech.\n\nThis compound conjugationgroup combines:\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª The auxiliary verb ~werden~ in Konjunktiv I conjugation\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª The ~infinitive~ of the main verb\n\nThe result: \"Er sagte, er ~werde~ morgen ~kommen~\" (He said he would come tomorrow) or \"Sie berichtete, es ~werde~ regnen\" (She reported that it would rain).\n\nLike other Konjunktiv I conjugations, the Futur Konjunktiv I appears primarily in formal writingâ€”journalism, academic prose, and literary narrationâ€”where German carefully distinguishes between what the writer predicts directly and what the writer reports others as predicting.`Formation`The Futur Konjunktiv I combines the Konjunktiv I of ~werden~ with the main verb's infinitive.`Konjunktiv I Conjugations of Werden`\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ich ~werde~ (I will â€” identical to indicative)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª du ~werdest~ (you will)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª er/sie/es ~werde~ (he/she/it will)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª wir ~werden~ (we will â€” identical to indicative)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ihr ~werdet~ (you all will â€” identical to indicative)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª sie/Sie ~werden~ (they/you formal will â€” identical to indicative)\n\nThe distinctive conjugations are ~werde~ (1s/3s) and ~werdest~ (2s). The plurals are identical to the indicative, which sometimes triggers substitution with ~wÃ¼rde~ conjugations.`Complete Examples`\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª Er sagte, er ~werde~ das Buch ~lesen~. (He said he would read the book.)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª Sie berichtete, sie ~werde~ morgen ~ankommen~. (She reported she would arrive tomorrow.)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª Der Minister erklÃ¤rte, die Regierung ~werde~ handeln. (The minister declared the government would act.)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª Man teilte mit, es ~werde~ Ã„nderungen ~geben~. (It was announced there would be changes.)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª Er versprach, er ~werde~ es nie ~vergessen~. (He promised he would never forget it.)`The Third-Person Dominance`As with other Konjunktiv I conjugations, the Futur Konjunktiv I appears overwhelmingly in the third person. Indirect speech typically reports what ~others~ said about the future:\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª er/sie ~werde~ + infinitive\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª sie (plural) ~wÃ¼rden~ + infinitive (Konjunktiv II substitution)\n\nFirst-person conjugations are rare because they are identical to the indicativeâ€”and because speakers typically use the indicative to state their own future intentions directly.`When Konjunktiv II Substitutes`When Konjunktiv I conjugations are identical to the indicative, German substitutes Konjunktiv II (~wÃ¼rde~) to preserve the reported-speech signal:\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª Ambiguous: \"Sie sagten, sie ~werden~ kommen.\" (Did the writer or the speakers assert this?)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª Clear: \"Sie sagten, sie ~wÃ¼rden~ kommen.\" (Unambiguous reported speech)\n\nThis substitution is grammatically correct and extremely common, especially in the first person and all plural conjugations.`Futur Konjunktiv I vs. Futur Indikativ`Compare these sentences:\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~Indicative~: \"Der Sprecher sagt, das Wetter ~wird~ besser.\" â€” The writer endorses this as likely true.\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~Konjunktiv I~: \"Der Sprecher sagt, das Wetter ~werde~ besser.\" â€” The writer reports the speaker's prediction without endorsing it.\n\nThe Konjunktiv I signals: \"This is what they say will happenâ€”I am not personally vouching for it.\" This distancing function is crucial in objective reporting.`Usage in Journalism and Formal Writing`The Futur Konjunktiv I is a hallmark of German journalistic style when reporting predictions, plans, and promises:\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª \"Der Kanzler kÃ¼ndigte an, die Regierung ~werde~ neue MaÃŸnahmen ~ergreifen~.\" = \"The Chancellor announced that the government would take new measures.\"\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª \"Laut Experten ~werde~ die Wirtschaft im nÃ¤chsten Jahr ~wachsen~.\" = \"According to experts, the economy will grow next year.\"\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª \"Die Firma teilte mit, sie ~werde~ 500 neue Stellen ~schaffen~.\" = \"The company announced it would create 500 new positions.\"\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª \"Der Wetterdienst prognostizierte, es ~werde~ am Wochenende ~schneien~.\" = \"The weather service predicted it would snow on the weekend.\"\n\nThe Konjunktiv I maintains journalistic neutralityâ€”the reporter conveys the prediction without endorsing its accuracy.`Differences from English`English handles reported future statements differently:\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~Verb-conjugation marking~: German marks reported speech on the verb itself (~werde~ vs. ~wird~). English relies on context and sometimes \"backshifts\" will to would: \"He said he ~would~ come.\"\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~Ambiguity~: English \"He said he would come\" is ambiguousâ€”it could report \"I will come\" or express a conditional. German ~werde kommen~ unambiguously marks reported future.\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~Formality~: German Konjunktiv I is fully productive in formal registers. English has no equivalent dedicated conjugation for reported future.\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~Substitution~: German's wÃ¼rde substitution when Konjunktiv I matches indicative has no English parallel.`Relationship to Other Conjugationgroups`The Futur Konjunktiv I relates to several other conjugationgroups:\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~PrÃ¤sens Konjunktiv I~: Reports present states in indirect speech. \"Er sagt, er ~sei~ mÃ¼de.\"\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~Perfekt Konjunktiv I~: Reports past events in indirect speech. \"Er sagte, er ~habe~ das ~gemacht~.\"\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~Futur Konjunktiv I~: Reports future events in indirect speech. \"Er sagt, er ~werde~ ~kommen~.\"\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~Futur Indikativ~: States future events directly. \"Er ~wird~ ~kommen~.\"\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~Futur Konjunktiv II~: Expresses hypothetical future. \"Er ~wÃ¼rde~ ~kommen~, wenn...\"\n\nThe Konjunktiv I system provides a complete temporal framework for indirect speechâ€”past, present, and future.`Literary Examples`The Futur Konjunktiv I appears in German literature when characters' predictions, promises, or expectations are reported.`Goethe â€” The Sorrows of Young Werther (1774)`\"Du bist so gut, meiner Mutter zu sagen, daÃŸ ich ihr GeschÃ¤ft bestens betreiben und ihr ehstens Nachricht davon ~geben werde~.\" = \"Be so good as to tell my mother that I shall attend to her business as well as I can, and shall write to her about it soon.\"\n\nWerther asks Wilhelm to relay a messageâ€”a promise about future action. The ~werde geben~ conveys reported future: what Wilhelm should say Werther ~will do~.\n\n\"Es ~werde~ alles ~gut gehen~.\" = \"All will go on well.\"\n\nA reported assurance about the futureâ€”someone's prediction conveyed through subjunctive distance.`Kafka â€” The Trial (1925)`\"Man setze voraus, daÃŸ er damit einverstanden sei; wollte er einen andern Termin wÃ¼nschen, so ~wÃ¼rde~ man ihm, so gut es ginge, ~entgegenkommen~.\" = \"They assumed he would agree; should he wish a different time, they would accommodate him as best they could.\"\n\nKafka's bureaucratic world is full of reported arrangements. The court's message uses subjunctive conjugations to convey what \"they\" predict and promiseâ€”accommodation if K. requests a different time.\n\n\"Sie ~werden~ noch ~einsehn~, wie wahr das alles ist.\" = \"You will yet see how true all this is.\"\n\nThe guard's prediction to K. uses the indicative ~werden~, showing the guard's confident assertion rather than distanced reportage.`Mann â€” Death in Venice (1912)`\"Er sagte sich, daÃŸ er Venedig nie wieder ~sehen solle~, daÃŸ dies ein Abschied fÃ¼r immer ~sei~.\" = \"He told himself that he should never see Venice again, that this was a farewell forever.\"\n\nAschenbach's inner speech is reported using Konjunktiv I conjugations. The ~solle~ (Konjunktiv I of ~sollen~) and ~sei~ convey his own predictions to himselfâ€”what he believes ~will~ be the case.`Why the Futur Konjunktiv I Matters`The Futur Konjunktiv I is essential for:\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~Reading German journalism~: News articles use it constantly to report promises, predictions, and announcements without editorial endorsement.\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~Academic writing~: Scholarly prose employs it to cite predictions and forecasts from sources.\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~Formal announcements~: Official communications use it for attributed future statements.\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~Literary narration~: Authors use it to report characters' expectations and intentions.\n\nWhile less common than its present and perfect counterparts, the Futur Konjunktiv I completes the Konjunktiv I systemâ€”giving German a dedicated conjugationgroup for every temporal dimension of reported speech. Understanding it unlocks the full expressive range of formal German prose."
