            "value" : "`About`The ~Imperativ~ is German's mood of command. Where other conjugationgroups describe, report, or hypothesize, the Imperativ ~directs~â€”telling someone what to do, urging action, or issuing prohibitions.\n\nUnlike most German conjugationgroups, the Imperativ exists only in the second person (du, ihr, Sie) and 1p (wir). You cannot command yourself in third person, nor can you command someone who isn't present. This gives the Imperativ its distinctive four-conjugation structure:\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~du-conjugation~ (informal singular): Geh! (Go!)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~ihr-conjugation~ (informal plural): Geht! (Go!)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~Sie-conjugation~ (formal singular/plural): Gehen Sie! (Go!)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~wir-conjugation~ (inclusive \"let's\"): Gehen wir! (Let's go!)\n\nThe Imperativ appears throughout daily lifeâ€”in instructions, recipes, signs, advertisements, and conversation. \"~Warte~ mal!\" (Wait a moment!), \"~Nimm~ das!\" (Take this!), and \"~Kommen~ Sie herein!\" (Come in!) are phrases every German learner encounters early and often.`Conjugation by Person``The Du-Conjugation: Informal Singular`The ~du-conjugation~ is the most common Imperativ and the simplest: take the verb stem (infinitive minus ~-en~) and use it directly. The pronoun ~du~ is typically omitted.\n\n~Weak verbs~:\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª machen â†’ ~Mach!~ (Make!/Do!)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª sagen â†’ ~Sag!~ (Say!)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª spielen â†’ ~Spiel!~ (Play!)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª kaufen â†’ ~Kauf!~ (Buy!)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª hÃ¶ren â†’ ~HÃ¶r!~ (Listen!)\n\nNote: Verbs with stems ending in -d, -t, or consonant clusters add ~-e~ for pronunciation: arbeiten â†’ ~Arbeite!~, Ã¶ffnen â†’ ~Ã–ffne!~\n\n~Strong verbs with eâ†’i/ie ablaut~:\nStrong verbs that change ~e~ to ~i~ or ~ie~ in the du/er conjugations of PrÃ¤sens Indikativ carry this change into the Imperativ:\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª sehen (siehst) â†’ $SIEh$! (See!/Look!)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª nehmen (nimmst) â†’ $NImm$! (Take!)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª geben (gibst) â†’ $GIb$! (Give!)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª lesen (liest) â†’ $lIEs$! (Read!)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª essen (isst) â†’ $Iss$! (Eat!)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª sprechen (sprichst) â†’ $sprIch$! (Speak!)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª helfen (hilfst) â†’ $hIlf$! (Help!)\n\n~Strong verbs with aâ†’Ã¤ ablaut~:\nVerbs with ~aâ†’Ã¤~ ablaut in PrÃ¤sens Indikativ do ~not~ take the ablaut umlaut in the Imperativ:\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª fahren (fÃ¤hrst) â†’ ~Fahr!~ (Drive!) â€” not *FÃ¤hr!\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª schlafen (schlÃ¤fst) â†’ ~Schlaf!~ (Sleep!) â€” not *SchlÃ¤f!\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª laufen (lÃ¤ufst) â†’ ~Lauf!~ (Run!) â€” not *LÃ¤uf!\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª tragen (trÃ¤gst) â†’ ~Trag!~ (Carry!) â€” not *TrÃ¤g!\n\nThis asymmetry reflects the Imperativ's ancient originsâ€”it preserves the original stem vowel from before ablaut developed.`The Ihr-Conjugation: Informal Plural`The ~ihr-conjugation~ addresses multiple people informally. It is identical to the ihr-conjugation of PrÃ¤sens Indikativ, with the pronoun omitted:\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª machen â†’ ~Macht!~ (Make!/Do!)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª sagen â†’ ~Sagt!~ (Say!)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª sehen â†’ ~Seht!~ (See!)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª nehmen â†’ ~Nehmt!~ (Take!)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª kommen â†’ ~Kommt!~ (Come!)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª gehen â†’ ~Geht!~ (Go!)\n\nThe ihr-conjugation is straightforward: no ablaut irregularities, no umlaut concerns. Whatever the verb does in \"ihr macht,\" it does in the Imperativ \"Macht!\"â€”just drop the pronoun.`The Sie-Conjugation: Formal Address`The ~Sie-conjugation~ serves for formal address, whether singular or plural. It uses the Infinitiv followed by the pronoun ~Sie~:\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª machen â†’ ~Machen Sie!~ (Make!/Do!)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª sagen â†’ ~Sagen Sie!~ (Say!)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª sehen â†’ ~Sehen Sie!~ (See!)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª nehmen â†’ ~Nehmen Sie!~ (Take!)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª kommen â†’ ~Kommen Sie!~ (Come in!)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª gehen â†’ ~Gehen Sie!~ (Go!)\n\nThe Sie-conjugation is also the most polite Imperativ conjugation. Adding ~bitte~ (please) makes it courteous: \"~Kommen Sie bitte~ herein!\" (Please come in!)\n\nNote that ~Sie~ is always capitalized in writing, distinguishing formal \"you\" from \"sie\" (they/she).`The Wir-Conjugation: \"Let's...\" Suggestions`The ~wir-conjugation~ expresses suggestions or exhortations that include the speakerâ€”equivalent to English \"Let's...\":\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª gehen â†’ ~Gehen wir!~ (Let's go!)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª anfangen â†’ ~Fangen wir an!~ (Let's begin!)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª essen â†’ ~Essen wir!~ (Let's eat!)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª singen â†’ ~Singen wir!~ (Let's sing!)\n\nLike the Sie-conjugation, the wir-conjugation uses the Infinitiv. The pronoun ~wir~ follows the verb directly.`The Irregular Imperative of sein`The verb ~sein~ (be) has unique Imperativ conjugations:\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª du-conjugation: ~Sei!~ (Be!)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ihr-conjugation: ~Seid!~ (Be!)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª Sie-conjugation: ~Seien Sie!~ (Be!)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª wir-conjugation: ~Seien wir!~ (Let's be!)\n\nThese conjugations derive from the old subjunctive of ~sein~, not from a regular Imperativ pattern. \"~Sei~ ruhig!\" (Be quiet!), \"~Seid~ vorsichtig!\" (Be careful!), and \"~Seien~ Sie willkommen!\" (Be welcome!) are common expressions.`Separable-Prefix Verbs`Verbs with separable prefixes split in the Imperativ, with the prefix moving to the end:\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ankommen â†’ ~Komm an!~ (Arrive!)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª aufmachen â†’ ~Mach auf!~ (Open!)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª aufpassen â†’ ~Pass auf!~ (Watch out!)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª mitkommen â†’ ~Komm mit!~ (Come along!)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª zuhÃ¶ren â†’ ~HÃ¶r zu!~ (Listen!)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª anfangen â†’ ~Fang an!~ / ~Fangt an!~ / ~Fangen Sie an!~\n\nThis separation mirrors the behavior in main clauses: the prefix moves to clause-final position.`Negative Commands`Negative commands use ~nicht~ (not) or ~kein~ (no/none):\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~Geh nicht!~ (Don't go!)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~Mach das nicht!~ (Don't do that!)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~Sprich nicht so laut!~ (Don't speak so loudly!)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~Fahr nicht so schnell!~ (Don't drive so fast!)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~Hab keine Angst!~ (Don't be afraid! â€” lit. \"Have no fear!\")\n\nUnlike Spanish, German lacks a bespoke negative imperative conjugation. The standard Imperativ, combined with ~nicht~, suffice.`Differences from English`While both languages have imperative moods, four difference between ğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª-Imperativ and ğŸ´ó §ó ¢ó ¥ó ®ó §ó ¿-imperative stand out:\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª/ğŸ´ó §ó ¢ó ¥ó ®ó §ó ¿ ~Four conjugations vs. one~: English has a single imperative conjugation for all addressees, 2s, 1p, or 2p. ~Go! Let's go! Go!~ German distinguishes du/ihr/Sie/wir, encoding social relationships in the verb conjugation itself.\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª/ğŸ´ó §ó ¢ó ¥ó ®ó §ó ¿ ~Stem-vowel changes~: German strong verbs with eâ†’i/ie ablaut carry this change into the du-Imperativ (N$Im$m!, G$Ib$!, L$IEs$!). English imperatives show no such alternation.\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª/ğŸ´ó §ó ¢ó ¥ó ®ó §ó ¿ ~Formality marking~: The Sie-conjugation Imperativ explicitly marks formal registerâ€”\"Kommen Sie!\" vs. \"Komm!\"â€”while English relies on context or additional words.\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª/ğŸ´ó §ó ¢ó ¥ó ®ó §ó ¿ ~Subject inclusion~: German Sie- and wir-conjugations include their pronouns (\"Gehen Sie!\", \"Gehen wir!\"), while English imperatives typically omit subjects. The English \"Let's go\" uses a dummy \"let\" where German simply inverts: \"Gehen wir!\"`Historical Development`The imperative is among the oldest and most stable verb conjugations in any language. Proto-Indo-European had a dedicated imperative stem, and its reflexes appear in the earliest Germanic texts.\n\nIn Old High German (c. 750-1050 AD), the Imperativ already showed the essential patterns visible today. The ~Hildebrandslied~ (c. 830 AD) contains Imperativ conjugations like \"~gib~\" (give) and \"~hilf~\" (help), conjugations unchanged over nearly 1,200 years.\n\nThe ~Tatian~ translation (c. 830 AD), a Gospel harmony, preserves numerous Imperativs in religious instruction:\n\n\"~Gib~ uns hiutu unsaz emizzÃ®gaz prÃ´t.\" = \"~Give~ us this day our daily bread.\"\n\nThe conjugation ~gib~ is identical to that of the modern German Imperativâ€”one of countless examples of the Imperativ's remarkable stability across the centuries.`Literary Examples`The Imperativ appears in German literature whenever characters address each other directlyâ€”in commands, pleas, and exhortations.`Goethe â€” The Sorrows of Young Werther (1774)`\"~Borge~ mir die Pistolen fÃ¼r eine Reise.\" = \"~Lend~ me those pistols for a journey.\"\n\nWerther's final request to Albert uses the du-conjugation Imperativ ~borge~ (lend), the familiar address appropriate between friendsâ€”though the \"journey\" Werther contemplates is his last.\n\n\"~SchÃ¤mt~ euch, ihr NÃ¼chternen!\" = \"~Shame~ upon you, ye sages!\"\n\nThe ihr-conjugation imperative ~schÃ¤mt~ addresses multiple recipientsâ€”the \"sober\" rationalists Werther criticizes for lacking emotional depth. The reflexive pronoun ~euch~ completes the construction.`Kafka â€” The Trial (1925)`\"~Gehn~ Sie in Ihr Zimmer und ~warten~ Sie.\" = \"~Go~ into your room and ~wait~ there.\"\n\nThe guard's command to Josef K. uses the formal Sie-Imperativ twiceâ€”maintaining official register even while arresting him. The bureaucratic politeness of \"~Gehen Sie~\" makes the command more chilling, not less.\n\n\"~LaÃŸt~ mich, zum Teufel!\" = \"~Let go~ of me, for God's sake!\"\n\nK.'s outburst uses the ihr-conjugation imperative ~laÃŸt~ (modern spelling: ~lasst~), addressing the guards collectively. The oath \"zum Teufel\" (literally, \"to the devil\") intensifies his desperation.`Mann â€” Death in Venice (1912)`\"~Sei~ gesegnet!\" = \"God ~bless~ you!\" (lit. \"~Be~ blessed!\")\n\nAschenbach's silent farewell to Tadzio uses the du-conjugation of ~sein~'s Imperativâ€”~sei~. The intimate conjugation reflects his private feelings toward the boy, even as he maintains outward decorum.`Why the Imperativ Matters`The Imperativ is the voice of direct action, facilitating the:\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª Giving of instructions (~Mach das so!~)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª Making of requests (~Gib mir bitte...~)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª Issuance of warnings (~Pass auf!~)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª Offering of invitations (~Komm herein!~)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª Expression of encouragement (~Versuch es noch einmal!~)\n\nMastering the Imperativ means mastering the art of German discourseâ€”knowing when to use the familiar ~du~-conjugation with friends, the ~ihr~-conjugation with groups, and the formal ~Sie~-conjugation with strangers and superiors. It encodes not just commands but social relationships, register, and respect."
