            "value" : "~Mood~ expresses the speaker's attitude toward the action or some other information about the action not involving tense or voice.\n\nLike tense, mood is one component of many conjugationgroups. For example, %PrÃ¤sens Indikativ% has PrÃ¤sens tense, implied Aktiv voice, and Indikativ mood.\n\nEnglish-speaking German learners might benefit from identification of the English moods, so here they are:\n\nğŸ´ó §ó ¢ó ¥ó ®ó §ó ¿ ~Indicative~: This mood expresses no attitude and is the default, most widely used mood. Example: \"The indicative mood ~expresses~ no attitude.\"\nğŸ´ó §ó ¢ó ¥ó ®ó §ó ¿ ~Subjunctive~: This mood, largely avoided in informal English, expresses wishes, demands, unreality, or hypotheticality. Examples: \"The low temperature necessitates that the skier ~wear~ a hat.\" \"If I ~were~ a humpback whale, I would divide my time between HawaiÊ»i and Alaska.\"\nğŸ´ó §ó ¢ó ¥ó ®ó §ó ¿ ~Conditional~: This mood expresses contingency. Example: \"In the absence of other constraints, Josh Adams ~would spend~ every waking hour on development of ~Konjugieren~.\"\nğŸ´ó §ó ¢ó ¥ó ®ó §ó ¿ ~Imperative~: This mood expresses a command. Example: \"Let's conjugate some verbs.\"\n\nGerman mood names differ somewhat from English mood names, but the uses are quite similar.\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~Indikativ~: This mood states facts and describes reality, just like English indicative. Example: \"Die Katze ~sitzt~ auf der Tastaturâ€”schon wieder.\" = \"The cat ~is sitting~ on the keyboardâ€”again.\"\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~Konjunktiv I~: This mood is primarily used for indirect speech (~indirekte Rede~)â€”reporting what someone else said. Unlike English, which shifts reported speech into past tense, German preserves the original tense but changes the conjugation. Example: Direct: \"Ich war das nicht.\" â†’ Indirect: \"Das Kind sagte, es ~sei~ das nicht gewesen.\" = \"The child said it ~wasn't~ him.\" Konjunktiv I appears mainly in journalism and formal writing. When Konjunktiv I conjugations are identical to indicative, which happens in 1s, 1p, and 3p, speakers substitute Konjunktiv II to maintain clarity.\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~Konjunktiv II~, also called ~Konjunktiv II~: This mood expresses hypothetical or contrary-to-fact situations, like English conditional. Example: \"Wenn ich unsichtbar ~wÃ¤re~, ~wÃ¼rde~ ich trotzdem in der Schlange warten.\" = \"If I ~were~ invisible, I ~would~ still wait in line.\"\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~Imperativ~: This mood expresses commands, just like English imperative. Example: \"~Iss~ deinen Brokkoli!\" = \"~Eat~ your broccoli!\"\n\nHere are the German conjugationgroups arranged by mood:\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~Indikativ~: %PrÃ¤sens Indikativ%, %PrÃ¤teritum Indikativ%, %Perfekt Indikativ%\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~Konjunktiv I~: %PrÃ¤sens Konjunktiv I%, %Perfekt Konjunktiv I%\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~Konjunktiv II~: %PrÃ¤teritum Konjunktiv II%\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~Imperativ~: %Imperativ%"
