            "state" : "translated",
            "value" : "`About`The ~Perfekt Konjunktiv I~ is German's primary conjugationgroup for reporting past events in indirect speech. While the PrÃ¤sens Konjunktiv I reports what someone says or thinks in the present, the Perfekt Konjunktiv I reports what someone said ~happened~â€”completed actions viewed through the lens of reported speech.\n\nThis compound conjugationgroup combines:\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª The auxiliary verb (~haben~ or ~sein~) in Konjunktiv I conjugation\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª The ~Perfektpartizip~ (past participle) of the main verb\n\nThe result: \"Er sagte, er ~habe~ das Buch gelesen\" (He said he had read the book) or \"Sie berichtete, sie ~sei~ nach Berlin gefahren\" (She reported that she had gone to Berlin).\n\nThe Perfekt Konjunktiv I appears primarily in formal writingâ€”journalism, academic prose, legal documents, and literary narrationâ€”where German maintains a careful distinction between what the writer asserts directly and what the writer reports others as having said.`Conjugation`The Perfekt Konjunktiv I is built from two components: the Konjunktiv I conjugation of the auxiliary and the Perfektpartizip.`Konjunktiv I Conjugations of Haben`The auxiliary ~haben~ in Konjunktiv I:\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ich ~habe~ (I have â€” identical to indicative)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª du ~habest~ (you have)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª er/sie/es ~habe~ (he/she/it has)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª wir ~haben~ (we have â€” identical to indicative)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ihr ~habet~ (you all have)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª sie/Sie ~haben~ (they/you formal have â€” identical to indicative)\n\nNote that 1s, 1p, and 3p are identical to the indicative. In these cases, speakers often substitute Konjunktiv II conjugations (~hÃ¤tte~) or the ~wÃ¼rde~ construction to maintain the subjunctive distinction.`Konjunktiv I Conjugations of sein`The auxiliary ~sein~ in Konjunktiv I:\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ich ~sei~ (I be)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª du ~seist~ / ~seiest~ (you be)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª er/sie/es ~sei~ (he/she/it be)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª wir ~seien~ (we be)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ihr ~seiet~ (you all be)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª sie/Sie ~seien~ (they/you formal be)\n\nThe ~sein~ conjugations are all distinct from the indicative, making them unambiguous markers of reported speech.`Complete Examples by Verb Family``Weak Verbs`\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª machen â†’ Er sagte, er ~habe~ das ~gemacht~. (He said he had done that.)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª sagen â†’ Sie berichtete, sie ~habe~ nichts ~gesagt~. (She reported she had said nothing.)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª arbeiten â†’ Man behauptete, er ~habe~ hart ~gearbeitet~. (It was claimed he had worked hard.)`Strong Verbs`\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª sehen â†’ Er erklÃ¤rte, er ~habe~ sie ~gesehen~. (He explained he had seen her.)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª kommen â†’ Sie sagte, er ~sei~ spÃ¤t ~gekommen~. (She said he had come late.)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª gehen â†’ Der Zeuge sagte, sie ~sei~ ~gegangen~. (The witness said she had left.)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª nehmen â†’ Er behauptete, er ~habe~ nichts ~genommen~. (He claimed he had taken nothing.)`Mixed Verbs`\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª bringen â†’ Sie erzÃ¤hlte, er ~habe~ Blumen ~gebracht~. (She told that he had brought flowers.)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª denken â†’ Er sagte, er ~habe~ daran ~gedacht~. (He said he had thought of it.)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª wissen â†’ Sie meinte, sie ~habe~ es nicht ~gewusst~. (She said she hadn't known it.)`The Third-Person Dominance`In practice, the Perfekt Konjunktiv I appears overwhelmingly in the third person. This makes sense: indirect speech reports what ~others~ said, and those others are typically \"he,\" \"she,\" or \"they.\"\n\nThe most common conjugations you will encounter are:\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª er/sie ~habe~ + Perfektpartizip\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª er/sie ~sei~ + Perfektpartizip\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª sie (plural) ~hÃ¤tten~ + Perfektpartizip (Konjunktiv II substitution)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª sie (plural) ~seien~ + Perfektpartizip\n\nFirst-person conjugations (~ich habe~, ~wir haben~) are rare because they are identical to the indicativeâ€”and because one typically uses the indicative to report one's own past actions directly.`When Konjunktiv II Substitutes`When Konjunktiv I conjugations are identical to the indicative, German substitutes Konjunktiv II to preserve the reported-speech signal:\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª Indicative identical: \"Sie sagten, sie ~haben~ es gemacht.\" (ambiguousâ€”did the writer or the speakers assert this?)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª With substitution: \"Sie sagten, sie ~hÃ¤tten~ es gemacht.\" (clear reported speech)\n\nSimilarly:\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª \"Ich sagte, ich ~habe~ ihn gesehen.\" â†’ often becomes \"Ich sagte, ich ~hÃ¤tte~ ihn gesehen.\"\n\nThis substitution is grammatically correct and extremely common in both speech and writing.`Usage in Journalism and Formal Writing`The Perfekt Konjunktiv I is a hallmark of German journalistic style. Newspapers use it to report statements without endorsing their truth:\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª \"Der Minister erklÃ¤rte, die Regierung ~habe~ alle notwendigen MaÃŸnahmen ~ergriffen~.\" = \"The minister stated that the government had taken all necessary measures.\"\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª \"Die Polizei teilte mit, der VerdÃ¤chtige ~sei~ am Tatort ~gewesen~.\" = \"The police reported that the suspect had been at the crime scene.\"\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª \"Laut Augenzeugen ~habe~ das Fahrzeug eine rote Ampel ~Ã¼berfahren~.\" = \"According to eyewitnesses, the vehicle had run a red light.\"\n\nThe Konjunktiv I signals: \"This is what they saidâ€”I am not personally vouching for its accuracy.\" This distancing function is crucial in objective reporting.`Differences from English`English and German handle reported speech quite differently:\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~Verb-conjugation marking~: German marks reported speech on the verb itself (~habe~ vs. ~hat~). English relies on word order and context, with no dedicated reported-speech verb conjugations.\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~Tense shifting~: English typically \"backshifts\" reported speech: \"He said he ~had done~ it\" (past perfect for a simple past original). German maintains the original tense relationship but changes the mood: \"Er sagte, er ~habe~ es ~getan~\" (Perfekt Konjunktiv I).\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~Frequency~: The German Konjunktiv I system is fully productive in formal registers. English has no equivalent; the subjunctive (\"He insisted that she ~be~ present\") is limited and declining.\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~Ambiguity avoidance~: German's substitution of Konjunktiv II when Konjunktiv I is ambiguous has no English parallelâ€”English simply tolerates the ambiguity.`Historical Development`The Konjunktiv I descends from the Proto-Germanic optative, which expressed wishes and possibilities. In Old High German (c. 750â€“1050), the subjunctive was used broadlyâ€”for wishes, commands, possibilities, and reported speech.\n\nThe ~Tatian~ translation (c. 830 AD) shows early examples of the subjunctive in reported speech contexts, though the distinction between Konjunktiv I and II had not yet fully crystallized.\n\nBy Middle High German (c. 1050â€“1350), the subjunctive had begun specializing: Konjunktiv I for reported speech and wishes, Konjunktiv II for counterfactuals. This specialization intensified in Early New High German, and by the 18th century, the modern system was largely in place.\n\nThe Perfekt Konjunktiv Iâ€”combining subjunctive auxiliary with past participleâ€”developed as German needed a way to report ~past~ events in indirect speech, paralleling the rise of compound tenses generally.`Literary Examples`The Perfekt Konjunktiv I appears throughout German literature, especially in narrative passages that report characters' thoughts and statements.`Goethe â€” The Sorrows of Young Werther (1774)`\"Es hieÃŸ, sie ~sei~ mit Herrn Schmidt auf die Wiese hinausgegangen.\" = \"It was said she had gone out to the meadow with Mr. Schmidt.\"\n\nGoethe uses ~sei gegangen~ (Perfekt Konjunktiv I with ~sein~) to report what \"was said\"â€”the narrator conveys village gossip without asserting its truth. The subjunctive maintains narrative distance.\n\n\"Er sagte, das ~sei~ sehr Ã¼bel von Lotten ~gewesen~.\" = \"He said that was very bad of Lotte.\"\n\nHere ~sei gewesen~ (Perfekt Konjunktiv I of ~sein~ itself) reports Albert's judgment about Lotte. The narrator attributes the opinion to Albert rather than endorsing it directly.`Kafka â€” The Trial (1925)`\"Man ~habe~ den Ausweg dieser rasch aufeinanderfolgenden Untersuchungen gewÃ¤hlt.\" = \"They said they had chosen this approach of rapidly successive examinations.\"\n\nKafka's bureaucratic world is full of reported speechâ€”characters constantly reference what \"they\" have said or decided. The Konjunktiv I (~habe gewÃ¤hlt~) signals that K. is reporting the court's claimed reasoning, not asserting it as fact.\n\n\"Die Waschfrau schwieg, als ~habe~ sie nichts ~gehÃ¶rt~.\" = \"The washerwoman was silent, as if she had heard nothing.\"\n\nThis comparative construction (~als habe~) uses Konjunktiv I to create a hypothetical comparisonâ€”she acted as though she had heard nothing.`Mann â€” Death in Venice (1912)`\"Ein Kritiker schrieb, daÃŸ sein Held 'die Konzeption einer intellektuellen MÃ¤nnlichkeit' ~sei~.\" = \"A critic wrote that his hero was 'the conception of an intellectual masculinity.'\"\n\nMann uses Konjunktiv I to report critical assessments of Aschenbach's literary characters. The subjunctive distances Mann from the critic's interpretation while accurately conveying it.`Why the Perfekt Konjunktiv I Matters`The Perfekt Konjunktiv I is essential for:\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~Reading German journalism~: News articles use it constantly to report statements, accusations, and claims without editorial endorsement.\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~Academic writing~: Scholarly prose employs it to cite sources and report others' arguments.\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~Literary analysis~: Recognizing Konjunktiv I helps readers distinguish a narrator's voice from reported character speech.\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~Formal communication~: Legal, diplomatic, and official documents rely on it for precision.\n\nWhile the Perfekt Konjunktiv I may seem advanced, understanding it unlocks a vast domain of formal German prose. It is the grammatical tool that lets German maintainâ€”with a single verb conjugationâ€”the crucial distinction between \"this happened\" and \"someone said this happened.\""
