            "value" : "`About`The ~PrÃ¤sens Indikativ~ (present indicative) is the workhorse of German conjugationâ€”the conjugation you will use more than any other. It expresses actions happening now, habitual actions, general truths, and even scheduled future events. Master this conjugationgroup, and you have mastered the foundation of German verb usage.\n\nUnlike English, which distinguishes between \"I sing\" (simple present) and \"I am singing\" (present progressive), German uses a single conjugation for both: ~Ich singe~. This simplicity means fewer conjugations to learn, but it also means the PrÃ¤sens Indikativ carries a heavier communicative load than its English counterpart.\n\nThe PrÃ¤sens Indikativ consists of six conjugationsâ€”one for each combination of person (1st, 2nd, 3rd) and number (singular, plural). Each conjugation combines the verb's stem with a characteristic ending:\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~ich~ (I): stem + ~-e~\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~du~ (you, informal singular): stem + ~-st~\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~er/sie/es~ (he/she/it): stem + ~-t~\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~wir~ (we): stem + ~-en~\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~ihr~ (you, informal plural): stem + ~-t~\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~sie/Sie~ (they/you formal): stem + ~-en~\n\nThese endingsâ€”the same for nearly all verbsâ€”are the first conjugation pattern every German learner memorizes. They are also among the oldest patterns in the language, descended from Proto-Germanic endings spoken over two thousand years ago.`Conjugation by Verb Family`The basic pattern applies across all verb families, with strong verbs adding stem changes in 2s and 3s.`Weak Verbs: The Regular Pattern`~Weak verbs~ follow the standard pattern without any stem changes:\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~machen~ (make/do)\nâ€¢ ich mach~e~ â€¢ du mach~st~ â€¢ er/sie/es mach~t~\nâ€¢ wir mach~en~ â€¢ ihr mach~t~ â€¢ sie/Sie mach~en~\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~spielen~ (play)\nâ€¢ ich spiel~e~ â€¢ du spiel~st~ â€¢ er/sie/es spiel~t~\nâ€¢ wir spiel~en~ â€¢ ihr spiel~t~ â€¢ sie/Sie spiel~en~\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~sagen~ (say)\nâ€¢ ich sag~e~ â€¢ du sag~st~ â€¢ er/sie/es sag~t~\nâ€¢ wir sag~en~ â€¢ ihr sag~t~ â€¢ sie/Sie sag~en~\n\nThe vast majority of German verbsâ€”and all newly coined verbsâ€”are weak. Once you know the stem, conjugation is automatic.`Strong Verbs: Stem Changes in 2s and 3s`~Strong verbs~ often undergo ~ablaut~â€”a vowel changeâ€”in 2s and 3s. The most common patterns are ~e â†’ i~, ~e â†’ ie~, and ~a â†’ Ã¤~:\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~geben~ (give) â€” e â†’ i:\nâ€¢ ich geb~e~ â€¢ du $gIbst$ â€¢ er/sie/es $gIbt$\nâ€¢ wir geb~en~ â€¢ ihr geb~t~ â€¢ sie/Sie geb~en~\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~sehen~ (see) â€” e â†’ ie:\nâ€¢ ich seh~e~ â€¢ du $sIEhst$ â€¢ er/sie/es $sIEht$\nâ€¢ wir seh~en~ â€¢ ihr seh~t~ â€¢ sie/Sie seh~en~\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~nehmen~ (take) â€” e â†’ i with consonant change:\nâ€¢ ich nehm~e~ â€¢ du $nIMMst$ â€¢ er/sie/es $nIMmt$\nâ€¢ wir nehm~en~ â€¢ ihr nehm~t~ â€¢ sie/Sie nehm~en~\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~fahren~ (drive) â€” a â†’ Ã¤:\nâ€¢ ich fahr~e~ â€¢ du $fÃ„hrst$ â€¢ er/sie/es $fÃ„hrt$\nâ€¢ wir fahr~en~ â€¢ ihr fahr~t~ â€¢ sie/Sie fahr~en~\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~halten~ (hold) â€” a â†’ Ã¤:\nâ€¢ ich halt~e~ â€¢ du $hÃ„ltst$ â€¢ er/sie/es $hÃ„lt$\nâ€¢ wir halt~en~ â€¢ ihr halt~et~ â€¢ sie/Sie halt~en~\n\nThese stem changes occur ~only~ in 2s and 3sâ€”never in the plural conjugations, and never in 1s. The pattern is remarkably consistent: if a strong verb changes its stem in PrÃ¤sens Indikativ, it changes only in ~du~ and ~er/sie/es~.`Mixed Verbs`~Mixed verbs~ show no stem changes in the PrÃ¤sens Indikativâ€”their ablaut appears only in the PrÃ¤teritum and Perfektpartizip:\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~bringen~ (bring)\nâ€¢ ich bring~e~ â€¢ du bring~st~ â€¢ er/sie/es bring~t~\nâ€¢ wir bring~en~ â€¢ ihr bring~t~ â€¢ sie/Sie bring~en~\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~denken~ (think)\nâ€¢ ich denk~e~ â€¢ du denk~st~ â€¢ er/sie/es denk~t~\nâ€¢ wir denk~en~ â€¢ ihr denk~t~ â€¢ sie/Sie denk~en~\n\nIn the PrÃ¤sens Indikativ, mixed verbs behave exactly like weak verbs.`-Ieren Verbs`Verbs ending in ~-ieren~, borrowed from French and Latin, follow the weak pattern:\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~studieren~ (study)\nâ€¢ ich studier~e~ â€¢ du studier~st~ â€¢ er/sie/es studier~t~\nâ€¢ wir studier~en~ â€¢ ihr studier~t~ â€¢ sie/Sie studier~en~\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~telefonieren~ (telephone)\nâ€¢ ich telefonier~e~ â€¢ du telefonier~st~ â€¢ er/sie/es telefonier~t~\nâ€¢ wir telefonier~en~ â€¢ ihr telefonier~t~ â€¢ sie/Sie telefonier~en~`Separable-Prefix Verbs`Verbs with ~separable prefixes~ split in main clauses, with the prefix moving to the end:\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~ankommen~ (arrive)\nâ€¢ ich komm~e~ ... an â€¢ du komm~st~ ... an â€¢ er/sie/es komm~t~ ... an\n\n\"Der Zug ~kommt~ um 15 Uhr ~an~.\" = \"The train arrives at 3 PM.\"\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~aufstehen~ (stand up, get up)\nâ€¢ ich steh~e~ ... auf â€¢ du steh~st~ ... auf â€¢ er/sie/es steh~t~ ... auf\n\n\"Ich ~stehe~ jeden Morgen um sechs Uhr ~auf~.\" = \"I get up at six o'clock every morning.\"\n\nIn subordinate clauses, the verb reunites with its prefix at the end: \"Ich weiÃŸ, dass der Zug um 15 Uhr ~ankommt~.\" = \"I know that the train arrives at 3 PM.\"`Inseparable-Prefix Verbs`Verbs with ~inseparable prefixes~ (be-, emp-, ent-, er-, ge-, miss-, ver-, zer-) never separate:\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~verstehen~ (understand)\nâ€¢ ich versteh~e~ â€¢ du versteh~st~ â€¢ er/sie/es versteh~t~\nâ€¢ wir versteh~en~ â€¢ ihr versteh~t~ â€¢ sie/Sie versteh~en~\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~bekommen~ (receive, get)\nâ€¢ ich bekomm~e~ â€¢ du bekomm~st~ â€¢ er/sie/es bekomm~t~\nâ€¢ wir bekomm~en~ â€¢ ihr bekomm~t~ â€¢ sie/Sie bekomm~en~`Highly Irregular Verbs`A handful of verbsâ€”the most frequently used in the languageâ€”have highly irregular PrÃ¤sens Indikativ conjugations:\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~sein~ (to be)\nâ€¢ ich $bIn$ â€¢ du $bIst$ â€¢ er/sie/es $Ist$\nâ€¢ wir $sInd$ â€¢ ihr $seid$ â€¢ sie/Sie $sInd$\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~haben~ (to have)\nâ€¢ ich hab~e~ â€¢ du $hAst$ â€¢ er/sie/es $hAt$\nâ€¢ wir hab~en~ â€¢ ihr hab~t~ â€¢ sie/Sie hab~en~\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~werden~ (to become)\nâ€¢ ich werd~e~ â€¢ du $wIrst$ â€¢ er/sie/es $wIrd$\nâ€¢ wir werd~en~ â€¢ ihr werd~et~ â€¢ sie/Sie werd~en~\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~wissen~ (to know)\nâ€¢ ich $wEIss$ â€¢ du $wEIsst$ â€¢ er/sie/es $wEIss$\nâ€¢ wir wiss~en~ â€¢ ihr wiss~t~ â€¢ sie/Sie wiss~en~\n\nThe modal verbs (~kÃ¶nnen~, ~mÃ¼ssen~, ~dÃ¼rfen~, ~sollen~, ~wollen~, ~mÃ¶gen~) also have irregular patterns, with vowel changes in the singular and no change in the plural. For example, ~kÃ¶nnen~: ich ~kann~, du ~kannst~, er ~kann~, but wir ~kÃ¶nnen~, ihr ~kÃ¶nnt~, sie ~kÃ¶nnen~.`Phonological Adjustments`German adjusts verb endings to maintain pronounceability:`Stems Ending in -s, -ÃŸ, -x, -z`When the stem ends in a sibilant, the 2s ~-st~ reduces to ~-t~ to avoid a tongue-twisting double sibilant:\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~reisen~ (travel): du rei~st~ (not *reisst)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~heiÃŸen~ (be called): du heiÃŸ~t~ (not *heiÃŸst)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~sitzen~ (sit): du sitz~t~ (not *sitzst)`Stems Ending in -t or -d`When the stem ends in ~-t~ or ~-d~, an ~-e-~ is inserted before endings beginning with a consonant to ease pronunciation:\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~arbeiten~ (work):\nâ€¢ ich arbeit~e~ â€¢ du arbeit~est~ â€¢ er/sie/es arbeit~et~\nâ€¢ wir arbeit~en~ â€¢ ihr arbeit~et~ â€¢ sie/Sie arbeit~en~\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~finden~ (find):\nâ€¢ ich find~e~ â€¢ du find~est~ â€¢ er/sie/es find~et~\nâ€¢ wir find~en~ â€¢ ihr find~et~ â€¢ sie/Sie find~en~\n\nNote: Strong verbs with stem changes typically do ~not~ add ~-e-~: ~halten~ â†’ du ~hÃ¤ltst~ (not *hÃ¤ltest), because the changed vowel creates a different phonetic environment.`Uses of the PrÃ¤sens Indikativ`The PrÃ¤sens Indikativ serves multiple functions in German:`Current Actions`Describing what is happening right now:\n\n\"Ich ~lese~ ein Buch.\" = \"I am reading a book.\" / \"I read a book.\"\n\"Was ~machst~ du?\" = \"What are you doing?\"\n\"Es ~regnet~.\" = \"It is raining.\"\n\nRemember: German does not distinguish between \"I read\" and \"I am reading\"â€”both are ~Ich lese~.`Habitual Actions`Describing regular, repeated activities:\n\n\"Ich ~spiele~ jeden Tag Tennis.\" = \"I play tennis every day.\"\n\"Sie ~trinkt~ morgens Kaffee.\" = \"She drinks coffee in the morning.\"\n\"Wir ~gehen~ sonntags in die Kirche.\" = \"We go to church on Sundays.\"`General Truths and Facts`Stating timeless realities:\n\n\"Die Erde ~dreht~ sich um die Sonne.\" = \"The Earth revolves around the sun.\"\n\"Wasser ~siedet~ bei 100 Grad.\" = \"Water boils at 100 degrees.\"\n\"Berlin ~liegt~ in Deutschland.\" = \"Berlin is located in Germany.\"`Scheduled Future`Expressing future events that are scheduled or certain, especially with a time expression:\n\n\"Der Zug ~fÃ¤hrt~ um 8 Uhr ~ab~.\" = \"The train departs at 8 o'clock.\"\n\"Morgen ~fliege~ ich nach Berlin.\" = \"Tomorrow I fly to Berlin.\"\n\"NÃ¤chste Woche ~beginnt~ der Kurs.\" = \"Next week the course begins.\"\n\nThis usage is more common in German than in English, where \"will\" or \"going to\" would typically be used.`Historical Present`Narrating past events with present-tense verbs for vividness:\n\n\"1945 ~endet~ der Zweite Weltkrieg.\" = \"In 1945, the Second World War ends.\"\n\"Da ~kommt~ plÃ¶tzlich ein Mann herein und ~sagt~...\" = \"Then suddenly a man comes in and says...\"\n\nThe historical present appears frequently in journalism, storytelling, and historical writing.`Differences from English`Several key differences distinguish the German PrÃ¤sens Indikativ from the English present tense:`No Progressive Aspect`German has no equivalent to the English progressive (\"I am doing\"). The sentence \"Ich lese\" means both \"I read\" and \"I am reading.\" Context determines which meaning applies:\n\n\"Was ~liest~ du?\" could mean:\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª \"What are you reading?\" (right now)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª \"What do you read?\" (habitually)\n\nIf emphasis on ongoing action is needed, German can add ~gerade~ (just now): \"Ich ~lese gerade~ ein Buch\" = \"I am reading a book (right now).\"`Future with Present Tense`German uses the present tense for scheduled future events far more readily than English:\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª \"Morgen ~fahre~ ich nach MÃ¼nchen.\" = \"Tomorrow I'm going/I'll go to Munich.\"\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª \"Das Konzert ~beginnt~ um 20 Uhr.\" = \"The concert starts/will start at 8 PM.\"\n\nWhile German has a future tense (~werden~ + infinitive), the present tense with a time expression is often preferred for concrete plans.`After \"Wenn\" (If/When)`In conditional and temporal clauses with ~wenn~, followed by another clause, German often uses present tense in both clauses where English uses present tense and then future tense:\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª \"Wenn er kommt, ~sage~ ich es ihm.\" = \"When he comes, I ~will tell~ him.\"\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª \"Wenn du es baust, ~kommen~ sie.\" = \"If you build it, they ~will come~.\"`Literary Examples`The PrÃ¤sens Indikativ permeates German literature, serving as the default narrative mode and the voice of reflection, dialogue, and timeless truth.`Goethe â€” The Sorrows of Young Werther (1774)`\"Wie froh ~bin~ ich, daÃŸ ich weg ~bin~!\" = \"How glad I am to be away!\"\n\nGoethe's opening line uses ~bin~ twiceâ€”the highly irregular 1s of ~sein~. Werther's emotional state (gladness) and his physical state (being away) are both expressed in the PrÃ¤sens Indikativ, capturing the immediacy of his feelings.\n\n\"Ich ~weiÃŸ~ nicht, ob tÃ¤uschende Geister um diese Gegend ~schweben~, oder ob die warme himmlische Phantasie in meinem Herzen ~ist~, die mir alles rings umher so paradiesisch ~macht~.\" = \"I do not know whether deceiving spirits haunt this region, or whether the warm celestial fancy is in my heart, that makes everything around me seem so like paradise.\"\n\nThis sentence weaves together multiple PrÃ¤sens Indikativ conjugations: ~weiÃŸ~ (1st singular of ~wissen~), ~schweben~ (3rd plural), ~ist~ (3rd singular of ~sein~), and ~macht~ (3rd singular). The present tense conveys Werther's ongoing uncertainty and the persistent enchantment of his surroundings.`Mann â€” Death in Venice (1912)`\"Gustav Aschenbach, oder von Aschenbach, wie seit seinem fÃ¼nfzigsten Geburtstag amtlich sein Name ~lautet~, ~hat~ an einem FrÃ¼hjahrsnachmittag des Jahres 19.. einen weiteren Spaziergang unternommen.\" = \"Gustav Aschenbach, or von Aschenbach, as his name has officially read since his fiftieth birthday, had undertaken a walk one spring afternoon of the year 19..\"\n\nMann's narrator uses ~lautet~ (3rd singular of ~lauten~, \"to read/sound\") and ~hat~ to establish facts that persist into the narrative present. The formal, measured quality of Mann's prose emerges partly from his precise deployment of indicative conjugations.\n\n\"Sein Ohr ~nimmt~ die unter den Laubplatanen des Spazierweges ~verflochtenen~ Stimmen der Gondoliere wahr.\" = \"His ear perceives the voices of the gondoliers intertwined beneath the plane trees of the promenade.\"\n\nThe verb ~nimmt~ (3rd singular of ~nehmen~, with the characteristic i-stem change) captures Aschenbach's sensory experience in the present moment.`Kafka â€” The Trial (1925)`\"Jemand ~muÃŸte~ Josef K. verleumdet haben, denn ohne daÃŸ er etwas BÃ¶ses ~getan hÃ¤tte~, wurde er eines Morgens verhaftet.\" = \"Someone must have been telling lies about Josef K., for without having done anything wrong, he was arrested one morning.\"\n\nWhile this famous opening uses past tenses for the arrest, notice that Kafka shifts to present indicative in the narrator's commentary throughout the novel.\n\n\"'Wer ~sind~ Sie denn?' ~fragt~ K. und ~sitzt~ gleich halb aufrecht im Bett.\" = \"'Who are you then?' K. asks and immediately sits half upright in bed.\"\n\nKafka's use of ~sind~, ~fragt~, and ~sitzt~â€”all PrÃ¤sens Indikativâ€”creates the unsettling immediacy that characterizes the novel. The reader experiences K.'s confusion in real time.`Historical Note`The PrÃ¤sens Indikativ endings you use today descend from Proto-Germanic, spoken roughly two thousand years ago, which in turn inherited them from Proto-Indo-European, the ancestor language spoken on the Pontic-Caspian steppe around 4000 BC.\n\nThe Proto-Germanic present indicative endings were approximately:\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª 1st singular: *~-Å~ â†’ Old High German ~-u/-o~ â†’ Middle High German ~-e~ â†’ Modern German ~-e~\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª 2nd singular: *~-izi~ â†’ Old High German ~-is~ â†’ Middle High German ~-est~ â†’ Modern German ~-st~\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª 3rd singular: *~-iÃ¾i~ â†’ Old High German ~-it~ â†’ Middle High German ~-et~ â†’ Modern German ~-t~\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª 1st plural: *~-amaz~ â†’ Old High German ~-amÄ“s/-Ä“m~ â†’ Middle High German ~-en~ â†’ Modern German ~-en~\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª 2nd plural: *~-iÃ¾~ â†’ Old High German ~-at/-et~ â†’ Middle High German ~-et~ â†’ Modern German ~-t~\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª 3rd plural: *~-anÃ¾i~ â†’ Old High German ~-ant~ â†’ Middle High German ~-ent~ â†’ Modern German ~-en~\n\nThe Old High German ~Tatian~ translation (c. 830 AD) preserves early conjugations:\n\n\"Ther heilant ~quimit~ zi themo brunnin\" = \"The Savior ~comes~ to the well.\"\n\nHere ~quimit~ (from ~queman~, ancestor of modern ~kommen~) shows the Old High German 3rd singular ending ~-it~, which would later simplify to ~-t~.\n\nThe stem-vowel changes in strong verbs (the ablaut in ~geben~ â†’ ~gibst~, ~sehen~ â†’ ~siehst~) are even older, tracing back to Proto-Indo-European vowel gradation. These patterns have survived largely intact for six millenniaâ€”a testament to their fundamental role in the Germanic verb system.`Why the PrÃ¤sens Indikativ Matters`The PrÃ¤sens Indikativ is where German conjugation begins. It is the conjugationgroup children learn first, the conjugationgroup that appears most frequently in speech and writing, and the conjugationgroup upon which other conjugationgroups build. The Perfekt Indikativ, for instance, combines the PrÃ¤sens Indikativ of ~haben~ or ~sein~ with the Perfektpartizip.\n\nMastering the PrÃ¤sens Indikativ means mastering the basic architecture of German verb conjugation:\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª The six-conjugation paradigm (ich, du, er/sie/es, wir, ihr, sie/Sie)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª The standard endings (-e, -st, -t, -en, -t, -en)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª The stem-change patterns in strong verbs (eâ†’i, eâ†’ie, aâ†’Ã¤)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª The phonological adjustments for stems ending in sibilants or dentals\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª The separation of separable prefixes in main clauses\n\nThese patterns recur throughout the German verb system. Learn them well in the PrÃ¤sens Indikativ, and you have a foundation for every other conjugationgroup.\n\nWhen you conjugate ~ich gehe~, ~du siehst~, or ~er kommt~, you are using conjugations that German speakers have used for over a millenniumâ€”the same basic patterns that Goethe used to write Werther's letters, that Kafka used to trap Josef K. in his nightmare, and that millions of German speakers use every day. The PrÃ¤sens Indikativ connects you to that living tradition."
