            "value" : "`About`The ~PrÃ¤teritum Indikativ~ (simple past indicative) is German's literary past tenseâ€”the conjugationgroup that dominates novels, fairy tales, news reports, and formal written narratives. While spoken German overwhelmingly prefers the Perfekt (\"Ich habe $gesUngen$\"), the PrÃ¤teritum (\"Ich $sAng$\") remains the hallmark of polished prose.\n\nThis division between spoken and written language gives the PrÃ¤teritum a distinctive character. When you read Goethe, Kafka, or any German novel, you encounter the PrÃ¤teritum on nearly every page. When you chat with a German friend, you rarely hear itâ€”except for a handful of very common verbs like ~sein~, ~haben~, and the modals.\n\nThe PrÃ¤teritum corresponds roughly to the English simple past (\"I $sAng$,\" \"I $WENT$,\" \"I $maDe$\"). Like English, German uses this conjugationgroup to narrate completed actions in the past without reference to the present. Unlike English, German maintains a sharp distinction between verb families: strong verbs are conjugated in the PrÃ¤teritum through ~ablaut~ (vowel change), while weak verbs are conjugated by addition of a ~-te~ suffix.\n\nUnderstanding the PrÃ¤teritum is essential for reading German literature, but it also illuminates the deep structure of the Germanic verb systemâ€”a structure German shares with English, Dutch, and the Scandinavian languages.`Conjugation by Verb Family`The PrÃ¤teritum reveals the fundamental divide between strong and weak verbs more clearly than any other conjugationgroup.`Strong Verbs: Ablaut Without -te`~Strong verbs~ are conjugated in the PrÃ¤teritum through ~ablaut~â€”a systematic vowel changeâ€”without adding the ~-te~ suffix. 1s and 3s have ~no ending at all~:\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~singen~ (sing) â€” i â†’ a:\nâ€¢ ich $sAng$ â€¢ du $sAngst$ â€¢ er/sie/es $sAng$\nâ€¢ wir $sAngen$ â€¢ ihr $sAngt$ â€¢ sie/Sie $sAngen$\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~sehen~ (see) â€” e â†’ a:\nâ€¢ ich $sAh$ â€¢ du $sAhst$ â€¢ er/sie/es $sAh$\nâ€¢ wir $sAhen$ â€¢ ihr $sAht$ â€¢ sie/Sie $sAhen$\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~geben~ (give) â€” e â†’ a:\nâ€¢ ich $gAb$ â€¢ du $gAbst$ â€¢ er/sie/es $gAb$\nâ€¢ wir $gAben$ â€¢ ihr $gAbt$ â€¢ sie/Sie $gAben$\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~nehmen~ (take) â€” e â†’ a (with consonant change):\nâ€¢ ich $nAhm$ â€¢ du $nAhmst$ â€¢ er/sie/es $nAhm$\nâ€¢ wir $nAhmen$ â€¢ ihr $nAhmt$ â€¢ sie/Sie $nAhmen$\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~kommen~ (come) â€” o â†’ a:\nâ€¢ ich $kAm$ â€¢ du $kAmst$ â€¢ er/sie/es $kAm$\nâ€¢ wir $kAmen$ â€¢ ihr $kAmt$ â€¢ sie/Sie $kAmen$\n\nNotice the distinctive pattern: 1s and 3s are identical and have no ending. This \"zero ending\" in the singular is one of the oldest features of the Germanic verb system.`Strong Verb Ablaut Patterns`Strong verbs fall into several ablaut classes, each with its characteristic vowel sequence. Here are the major patterns:\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~i â†’ a~ (the \"sing\" class): singen â†’ $sAng$, finden â†’ $fAnd$, beginnen â†’ $begAnn$, trinken â†’ $trAnk$\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~e â†’ a~ (the \"see\" class): sehen â†’ $sAh$, geben â†’ $gAb$, lesen â†’ $lAs$, sprechen â†’ $sprAch$\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~ie â†’ o~ (the \"offer\" class): bieten â†’ $bOt$, fliegen â†’ $flOg$, ziehen â†’ $zOg$\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~ei â†’ ie~ (the \"stay\" class): bleiben â†’ $blIEb$, schreiben â†’ $schrIEb$, steigen â†’ $stIEg$\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~a â†’ ie~ (the \"hold\" class): halten â†’ $hIElt$, fallen â†’ $fIEl$, lassen â†’ $lIEÃŸ$\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~e â†’ a~ with consonant change (the \"go\" class): gehen â†’ $gIng$, stehen â†’ $stAnd$\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~i â†’ a~ with consonant change (the \"sit\" class): sitzen â†’ $sAÃŸ$, liegen â†’ $lAg$\n\nThese patterns are not arbitraryâ€”they descend from Proto-Indo-European vowel gradations that were already systematic 6,000 years ago. When you learn that ~singen~ becomes $sAng$, you are learning a pattern shared by ~finden~ â†’ $fAnd$, ~trinken~ â†’ $trAnk$, and dozens of other verbs.`Weak Verbs: The -te Suffix`~Weak verbs~ are conjugated in the PrÃ¤teritum by addition of ~-te~ (and its variants) to the stem, with no vowel change:\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~machen~ (make/do):\nâ€¢ ich mach~te~ â€¢ du mach~test~ â€¢ er/sie/es mach~te~\nâ€¢ wir mach~ten~ â€¢ ihr mach~tet~ â€¢ sie/Sie mach~ten~\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~spielen~ (play):\nâ€¢ ich spiel~te~ â€¢ du spiel~test~ â€¢ er/sie/es spiel~te~\nâ€¢ wir spiel~ten~ â€¢ ihr spiel~tet~ â€¢ sie/Sie spiel~ten~\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~sagen~ (say):\nâ€¢ ich sag~te~ â€¢ du sag~test~ â€¢ er/sie/es sag~te~\nâ€¢ wir sag~ten~ â€¢ ihr sag~tet~ â€¢ sie/Sie sag~ten~\n\nThe endings are consistent:\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª 1st/3rd singular: ~-te~\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª 2nd singular: ~-test~\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª 1st/3rd plural: ~-ten~\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª 2nd plural: ~-tet~\n\nNote that 1s and 3s are again identicalâ€”a pattern shared with strong verbs.`Stems Ending in -t or -d`When a weak verb's stem ends in ~-t~ or ~-d~, an extra ~-e-~ is inserted for pronunciation:\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~arbeiten~ (work):\nâ€¢ ich arbeit~ete~ â€¢ du arbeit~etest~ â€¢ er/sie/es arbeit~ete~\nâ€¢ wir arbeit~eten~ â€¢ ihr arbeit~etet~ â€¢ sie/Sie arbeit~eten~\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~reden~ (talk):\nâ€¢ ich red~ete~ â€¢ du red~etest~ â€¢ er/sie/es red~ete~\nâ€¢ wir red~eten~ â€¢ ihr red~etet~ â€¢ sie/Sie red~eten~`Mixed Verbs: Ablaut Plus -te`~Mixed verbs~ combine both patterns: they undergo ablaut ~and~ add the ~-te~ suffix:\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~bringen~ (bring) â€” i â†’ a (with consonant change):\nâ€¢ ich $brAchte$ â€¢ du $brAchtest$ â€¢ er/sie/es $brAchte$\nâ€¢ wir $brAchten$ â€¢ ihr $brAchtet$ â€¢ sie/Sie $brAchten$\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~denken~ (think) â€” e â†’ a (with consonant change):\nâ€¢ ich $dAchte$ â€¢ du $dAchtest$ â€¢ er/sie/es $dAchte$\nâ€¢ wir $dAchten$ â€¢ ihr $dAchtet$ â€¢ sie/Sie $dAchten$\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~kennen~ (know) â€” e â†’ a:\nâ€¢ ich $kAnnte$ â€¢ du $kAnntest$ â€¢ er/sie/es $kAnnte$\nâ€¢ wir $kAnnten$ â€¢ ihr $kAnntet$ â€¢ sie/Sie $kAnnten$\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~wissen~ (know) â€” i â†’ u:\nâ€¢ ich $wUsste$ â€¢ du $wUsstest$ â€¢ er/sie/es $wUsste$\nâ€¢ wir $wUssten$ â€¢ ihr $wUsstet$ â€¢ sie/Sie $wUssten$\n\nThe mixed verbs are few but frequent. Note the consonant changes in ~bringen~ â†’ $brAchte$ and ~denken~ â†’ $dAchte$â€”these parallel English ~bring~ â†’ ~brought~ and ~think~ â†’ ~thought~, preserving a pattern from Proto-Germanic.`-Ieren Verbs`Verbs ending in ~-ieren~ follow the weak pattern:\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~studieren~ (study):\nâ€¢ ich studier~te~ â€¢ du studier~test~ â€¢ er/sie/es studier~te~\nâ€¢ wir studier~ten~ â€¢ ihr studier~tet~ â€¢ sie/Sie studier~ten~\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~telefonieren~ (telephone):\nâ€¢ ich telefonier~te~ â€¢ du telefonier~test~ â€¢ er/sie/es telefonier~te~\nâ€¢ wir telefonier~ten~ â€¢ ihr telefonier~tet~ â€¢ sie/Sie telefonier~ten~`Separable-Prefix Verbs`Verbs with ~separable prefixes~ split in main clauses, with the prefix moving to the end:\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~ankommen~ (arrive):\nâ€¢ ich $kAm$ ... an â€¢ du $kAmst$ ... an â€¢ er/sie/es $kAm$ ... an\n\n\"Der Zug ~kam~ um 15 Uhr ~an~.\" = \"The train arrived at 3 PM.\"\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~aufmachen~ (open):\nâ€¢ ich mach~te~ ... auf â€¢ du mach~test~ ... auf â€¢ er/sie/es mach~te~ ... auf\n\n\"Sie ~machte~ das Fenster ~auf~.\" = \"She opened the window.\"\n\nIn subordinate clauses, the verb reunites with its prefix: \"Ich $wEIÃŸ$, dass der Zug um 15 Uhr ~ankam~.\" = \"I know that the train arrived at 3 PM.\"`Inseparable-Prefix Verbs`Verbs with ~inseparable prefixes~ never separate:\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~verstehen~ (understand):\nâ€¢ ich ver$stAnd$ â€¢ du ver$stAndst$ â€¢ er/sie/es ver$stAnd$\nâ€¢ wir ver$stAnden$ â€¢ ihr ver$stAndt$ â€¢ sie/Sie ver$stAnden$\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~bekommen~ (receive):\nâ€¢ ich be$kAm$ â€¢ du be$kAmst$ â€¢ er/sie/es be$kAm$\nâ€¢ wir be$kAmen$ â€¢ ihr be$kAmt$ â€¢ sie/Sie be$kAmen$`Highly Irregular Verbs`The most common verbs have highly irregular PrÃ¤teritum conjugations:\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~sein~ (be):\nâ€¢ ich $wAr$ â€¢ du $wArst$ â€¢ er/sie/es $wAr$\nâ€¢ wir $wAren$ â€¢ ihr $wArt$ â€¢ sie/Sie $wAren$\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~haben~ (have):\nâ€¢ ich $hAtte$ â€¢ du $hAttest$ â€¢ er/sie/es $hAtte$\nâ€¢ wir $hAtten$ â€¢ ihr $hAttet$ â€¢ sie/Sie $hAtten$\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~werden~ (become):\nâ€¢ ich $wUrde$ â€¢ du $wUrdest$ â€¢ er/sie/es $wUrde$\nâ€¢ wir $wUrden$ â€¢ ihr $wUrdet$ â€¢ sie/Sie $wUrden$\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~tun~ (do):\nâ€¢ ich $tAt$ â€¢ du $tAtest$ â€¢ er/sie/es $tAt$\nâ€¢ wir $tAten$ â€¢ ihr $tAtet$ â€¢ sie/Sie $tAten$\n\nThese verbs are so frequent that their irregular conjugations must be memorized individually. Fortunately, their very frequency means you will encounter them constantly and learn them quickly.`Modal Verbs in PrÃ¤teritum`The ~modal verbs~ are conjugated in the PrÃ¤teritum with weak endings but often with vowel changes:\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~kÃ¶nnen~ (can) â†’ ich $kOnnte$, du $kOnntest$, etc.\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~mÃ¼ssen~ (must) â†’ ich $mUsste$, du $mUsstest$, etc.\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~dÃ¼rfen~ (may) â†’ ich $dUrfte$, du $dUrftest$, etc.\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~sollen~ (should) â†’ ich sollte, du solltest, etc. (no vowel change)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~wollen~ (want) â†’ ich wollte, du wolltest, etc. (no vowel change)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~mÃ¶gen~ (like) â†’ ich $mOchte$, du $mOchtest$, etc.\n\nNote: ~mÃ¶chte~ (\"would like\") is actually the PrÃ¤teritum Konjunktiv II of ~mÃ¶gen~, used so commonly as a polite request that many learners encounter it before the infinitive.`Written vs. Spoken German`One of the most striking features of modern German is the ~PrÃ¤teritumschwund~â€”the \"preterite flight\" or decline of the PrÃ¤teritum in spoken language, especially in southern Germany, Austria, and Switzerland.\n\nIn these regions, speakers almost exclusively use the Perfekt for past events:\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª Southern/spoken: \"Ich ~habe~ das Buch ~gelesen~.\" (I have read the book.)\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª Northern/written: \"Ich ~las~ das Buch.\" (I read the book.)\n\nBoth sentences describe the same past action, but the Perfekt dominates conversation while the PrÃ¤teritum dominates prose. This split is so pronounced that using the PrÃ¤teritum in casual speech (except for ~sein~, ~haben~, and modals) can sound overly formal or literary.\n\nEven in regions where PrÃ¤teritum survives in speech (parts of northern Germany), certain verbs resist it. ~Sein~ and ~haben~ retain their PrÃ¤teritum conjugations (~war~, ~hatte~) in speech everywhereâ€”saying \"Ich $BIN$ $geWESen$\" instead of \"Ich $WAR$\" sounds awkward even to southern speakers.\n\nFor learners, this means:\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~Reading~: You must know the PrÃ¤teritum to understand German literature.\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~Speaking~: Use Perfekt for most verbs, but ~war~, ~hatte~, and modal PrÃ¤teritum conjugations are natural in speech.\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~Writing~: Formal prose typically uses PrÃ¤teritum for narrative.`Differences from English`Despite surface similarities, the German PrÃ¤teritum and English simple past differ in important ways:`No Auxiliary Required`German PrÃ¤teritum is a ~synthetic~ conjugationgroupâ€”the past meaning is built into the verb itself. English often requires the auxiliary \"did\" for questions and negatives:\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª \"~Sangst~ du?\" = \"~Did~ you ~sing~?\"\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª \"Ich ~sang~ nicht.\" = \"I ~did~ not ~sing~.\"\n\nGerman simply conjugates the main verb; no auxiliary appears.`No Aspect Distinction`English distinguishes between simple past (\"I sang\") and past progressive (\"I was singing\"). German has only one conjugation:\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª \"Ich ~sang~.\" = \"I sang.\" / \"I was singing.\"\n\nContext determines whether the action was momentary or ongoing.`The Perfekt Alternative`Perhaps the biggest difference: German has ~two~ ways to express simple past meaning (PrÃ¤teritum and Perfekt), while English simple past has no direct competitor. This gives German speakers a stylistic choice English speakers lack.`Literary Examples`The PrÃ¤teritum is the narrative backbone of German literature. Every novel, every fairy tale, every historical account relies on it to carry the story forward.`Goethe â€” The Sorrows of Young Werther (1774)`\"Wie froh $BIN$ ich, daÃŸ ich weg $BIN$! Bester Freund, was ist das Herz des Menschen! Dich zu verlassen, den ich so liebe, von dem ich unzertrennlich $wAr$, und froh zu sein!\" = \"How glad I am to be away! Best of friends, what $Is$ the heart of man! To leave you, whom I so love, from whom I was inseparable, and yet to be happy!\"\n\nGoethe uses $WAR$ ($WAS$) hereâ€”the PrÃ¤teritum of ~sein~â€”to describe Werther's past state of inseparability from his friend, while the surrounding present-tense verbs ($BIN$, $ISt$) express his current emotional state. This interplay of tenses creates the letter's intimate, reflective tone.\n\n\"Wilhelm, was $ISt$ unserem Herzen die Welt ohne Liebe! Was eine Zauberlaterne $ISt$ ohne Licht! Kaum bringst du das LÃ¤mpchen hinein, so $schIEnen$ dir die buntesten Bilder an deine weiÃŸe Wand!\" = \"Wilhelm, what $Is$ the world to our hearts without love! What a magic lantern $Is$ without light! No sooner do you bring the little lamp inside than the most colorful pictures shine upon your white wall!\"\n\nWerther uses $schIEnen$ ($shone$, from ~scheinen~) in what might be called a hypothetical or generic pastâ€”describing what happens when one lights a magic lantern, expressed as if narrating a past event.`Mann â€” Death in Venice (1912)`\"Gustav Aschenbach oder von Aschenbach, wie seit seinem fÃ¼nfzigsten Geburtstag amtlich sein Name $lAutete$, $hAtte$ an einem FrÃ¼hlingsnachmittag des Jahres 19.., das unserem Kontinent monatelang eine so gefahrdrohende Miene $zEIgte$, von seiner Wohnung in der PrinzregentenstraÃŸe zu MÃ¼nchen aus allein einen weiteren Spaziergang $unternOmmen$.\" = \"Gustav Aschenbach, or von Aschenbach, as his name had officially read since his fiftieth birthday, had undertaken a rather long walk one spring afternoon of the year 19.., which for months had shown our continent so threatening a face, setting out alone from his apartment on the Prinzregentenstrasse in Munich.\"\n\nMann's magisterial opening sentence deploys four PrÃ¤teritum conjugations: $lAutete$ (sounded/read), $hAtte$ (had), $zEIgte$ (showed), and $unternOmmen$ (undertaken, in a Plusquamperfekt construction). This density of past-tense verbs establishes the retrospective narrative distance characteristic of literary German.\n\n\"Ein WindstoÃŸ $kAm$ auf, und die Zypressen $rAuschten$.\" = \"A gust of wind $arOse$, and the cypresses rustled.\"\n\nHere $kAm$ ($cAme$) and $rAuschten$ (rustled) demonstrate the PrÃ¤teritum's function in vivid scene-settingâ€”each verb captures a discrete past action that advances the narrative.`Kafka â€” The Trial (1925)`\"'Wer $sIND$ Sie?' fragte K. und $sAÃŸ$ gleich halb aufrecht im Bett.\" = \"'Who $ARE$ you?' K. asked and immediately $sAt$ half upright in bed.\"\n\nKafka uses fragte (asked) and $sAÃŸ$ ($sAt$) to narrate K.'s immediate reactions. The PrÃ¤teritum here creates the characteristic Kafkaesque toneâ€”events unfold with unsettling matter-of-factness, each past-tense verb recording what happened without emotional commentary.\n\n\"Der Mann, den er gar nicht $kAnnte$, $schIEn$ nicht aufgelegt, ihn lÃ¤nger als unbedingt notwendig in dem Zimmer zu dulden.\" = \"The man, whom he did not know at all, seemed disinclined to tolerate him in the room any longer than absolutely necessary.\"\n\nThe mixed verb ~kennen~ appears in its PrÃ¤teritum conjugation $kAnnte$ (knew), alongside $schIEn$ (seemed) from the strong verb ~scheinen~. Kafka's prose relies heavily on the PrÃ¤teritum to maintain its dreamlike narrative distance.`Historical Note`The PrÃ¤teritum's distinctive featuresâ€”ablaut in strong verbs, the ~-te~ suffix in weak verbs, the zero ending in 1st/3rd singular strong conjugationsâ€”all trace back to Proto-Germanic, spoken around the beginning of the Common Era.\n\nThe strong verb ablaut patterns descend from Proto-Indo-European vowel gradation, a system already ancient when the Germanic peoples emerged as a distinct group. The PIE verb root had different vowel grades (full, reduced, lengthened) that appeared in different conjugations. Germanic languages systematized these grades into the ablaut classes we see today:\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª PIE *~singÊ·-~ / *~songÊ·-~ / *~sungÊ·-~ â†’ Proto-Germanic *~singwan~ / *~sang~ / *~sungun-~ â†’ German ~singen~ / $sAng$ / $gesUngen$\n\nThe weak verb ~-te~ suffix has a different origin. It derives from a Proto-Germanic past-tense conjugation using the verb *~dÅn-~ (\"to do\"). Originally, the past tense of weak verbs was expressed with a suffixed \"do\", *~salbÅ-dedun~ (\"anointed-did\"), eventually fused into a single word and simplified to ~-te~. This \"dental suffix\" (so called because ~t~ and ~d~ are dental consonants) spread to all new verbs entering Germanic languagesâ€”which is why borrowed verbs like ~telefonieren~ follow the weak pattern.\n\nThe Old High German ~Tatian~ translation (c. 830 AD) shows early PrÃ¤teritum conjugations:\n\n\"Inti her $gIang$ in thia samanungu\" = \"And he ~went~ into the synagogue.\"\n\nThe verb $gIang$ (went, from ~gangan~) shows the Old High German PrÃ¤teritum with its characteristic ablaut. The ancestor of modern ~gehen~ â†’ $gIng$ is clearly visible.\n\nThe ~Hildebrandslied~ (c. 830 AD) opens with PrÃ¤teritum narration:\n\n\"Ik $gIhÃ´rta$ Ã°at seggen\" = \"I ~heard~ (it) said.\"\n\nHere $gIhÃ´rta$ (heard) shows the weak PrÃ¤teritum pattern with ~-ta~ (later ~-te~), already established 1,200 years ago.`Why the PrÃ¤teritum Indikativ Matters`The PrÃ¤teritum Indikativ opens the door to German literature. Without it, Goethe's Werther, Kafka's Josef K., and Mann's Aschenbach would remain inaccessible. Every German novel you will ever read depends on this conjugationgroup to carry its narrative.\n\nBut the PrÃ¤teritum also reveals the deep architecture of the Germanic verb system. The split between strong verbs (ablaut) and weak verbs (~-te~) is one of the defining features of the Germanic language family. When you learn that ~singen~ becomes ~sang~ and ~machen~ becomes ~machte~, you are learning the same patterns that shape English ~sing~/~sang~ and ~make~/~made~, Dutch ~zingen~/~zong~ and ~maken~/~maakte~, Swedish ~sjunga~/~sjÃ¶ng~ and ~gÃ¶ra~/~gjorde~.\n\nFor practical communication, the Perfekt may suffice. But for reading, for writing, and for understanding how German works at its deepest level, the PrÃ¤teritum is indispensable. It is the tense of storytelling, the tense of history, the tense of the written word.\n\nMaster it, and you gain access not only to German literature but to the living history of the Germanic languages themselvesâ€”a history stretching back through Old High German monks, through Gothic warriors, through Proto-Germanic wanderers, all the way to the Indo-European speakers who first established the ablaut patterns you use today."
