        "en" : {
          "stringUnit" : {
            "state" : "translated",
            "value" : "In linguistics, ~tense~ refers to the ~time~ that an action encoded in a verb occurred, occurs, or will occur. Like English, German has three tenses: ~PrÃ¤sens~ (present), ~PrÃ¤teritum~ (past), and ~Futur~ (future).\n\nTense is one component of many conjugationgroups. For example, PrÃ¤sens Aktiv Indikativ has PrÃ¤sens tense, Aktiv voice, and Indikativ mood. The Aktiv voice is implicit for conjugationgroups featuring it, and, unlike some sources, ~Konjugieren~ omits the word Aktiv from conjugationgroup names, for example %PrÃ¤sens Indikativ%.\n\nHere are the German conjugationgroups arranged by tense:\n\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~PrÃ¤sens~: %PrÃ¤sens Indikativ%, %PrÃ¤sens Konjunktiv I%, %PrÃ¤sens Partizip%\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~PrÃ¤teritum~: %PrÃ¤teritum Indikativ%, %PrÃ¤teritum Konjunktiv II%, %Perfekt Indikativ%, %Perfekt Konjunktiv I%, %Perfekt Partizip%\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª ~Futur~: %Futur Indikativ%, %Futur Konjunktiv I%, %Futur Konjunktiv II%`Commentary`The ~Perfektpartizip~ is in the PrÃ¤teritum ğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª item because this conjugationgroup inherently describes a completed action. In \"$gesUngen$\" ($sUng$), the singing is finishedâ€”a past-oriented meaning. This contrasts with the ~PrÃ¤senspartizip~, for example \"singend\" (singing), which describes an ongoing action.\n\nThe ~Imperativ~ doesn't fit neatly into tense categories. Commands like \"Sing!\" are directed at the present moment but don't describe past, present, or future actions in the traditional sense. Linguists sometimes call this \"tenseless\" or associate it loosely with present tense."
