        "en" : {
          "stringUnit" : {
            "state" : "translated",
            "value" : "`Verb`A ~verb~ is a kind of word that expresses an action. For example, in the German sentence \"Robert $sAng$ in London.\", \"%singen%\" is the verb. Likewise, in the English sentence \"Robert $sAng$ in London.\", \"to sing\" is the verb.`Conjugation`A conjugation is a modification, or non-modification, of a verb for a specific purpose. For example, \"$hAst$\" and \"$hAst$\" are conjugations of the German and Early Modern English verbs \"%haben%\" and \"to have\", respectively, indicating that the verb is associated with an informal, second-person-singular subject pronoun (\"du\" or \"thou\") and that the action described, the act of possession, takes place (or is taking place) in the present.`Conjugationgroup`A ~conjugationgroup~ is a related family of one, two, four, or six conjugations. You have already seen one conjugationgroup, Infinitiv (infinitive), in the examples of \"%singen%\", \"%haben%\", \"to sing\", and \"to have\". In German and English, the Infinitiv is the reference conjugation for verbs and therefore the one you look up in a dictionary. In both languages, an Infinitiv can also represent the act of doing something.\\n\\n\"Ich $BIN$ gezwungen, die Verbkonjugationen zu ~lernen~.\" = \"I $AM$ compelled ~to study~ verb conjugations.\"\\n\\nThe uses of some German and English conjugationgroups closely correspond, as with Infinitiv/infinitive, but the uses of some do not. Consider this example:\\n\\n\"I eat.\" != \"Ich esse.\"\\n\\nIn this example, the German speaker might be currently eating, but the English speaker is describing a habitual action and is not necessarily eating at this moment. The %PrÃ¤sens Indikativ%, the conjugationgroup demonstrated here, therefore has broader application than the similarly named Present Indicative.\\n\\nBecause of the inexact correspondence between German and English conjugationgroups, Konjugieren displays German conjugationgroup names by default, but there is a setting in the Settings tab to cause Konjugieren to display English conjugationgroup names, which are perhaps more familiar to the English-speaking target audience of Konjugieren.\\n\\nThe three conjugationgroups with one member each are Infinitiv, %Perfektpartizip% and %PrÃ¤senspartizip%.\\n\\nThe German conjugationgroup %Imperativ% has four members. Its English cousin, imperative, has two.\\n\\nAll other conjugationgroups have six members. You $sAW$ earlier $sAng$. This is a member of the conjugationgroup %PrÃ¤teritum Indicativ%. Here are all six members of that conjugationgroup for %singen%:\\n\\n$sAng$, $sAngst$, $sAng$, $sAngen$, $sAngt$, $sAngen$\\n\\nThe developer of Konjugieren coined the term \"conjugationgroup\" in late 2025, but the concept has existed for 5,000 years, if not longer. Some language commentators use the word \"tense\" for this concept, but, for reasons described later, \"tense\" has a precise meaning that is not broad enough for this important concept.`Subject Pronoun`A ~subject pronoun~ is a word that stands in for the subject in a sentence. The subject is the actor. In English, the subject pronouns in widespread use are ~I~, ~you~, ~he/she/it/one~, ~we~, ~you/y'all~, and ~they~. The English subject pronouns ~ye~ and ~thou~ have been in decline since the Elizabethan period, which is too bad for German learners because they are cognate with (related to) the German subject pronouns ~ihr~ and ~du~.\\n\\nSubject pronouns correspond to the ~singular~ or ~plural~ number and to the ~first person~, ~second person~, or ~third person~.\\n\\nEnglish subject pronouns follow. Abbreviations of the person-number combinations are in parentheses.\\n\\nğŸ´ó §ó ¢ó ¥ó ®ó §ó ¿ first person, singular (1s): ~I~\\nğŸ´ó §ó ¢ó ¥ó ®ó §ó ¿ second person, singular (2s): ~you~\\nğŸ´ó §ó ¢ó ¥ó ®ó §ó ¿ third person, singular (3s): ~he/she/it/one~\\nğŸ´ó §ó ¢ó ¥ó ®ó §ó ¿ first person, plural (1p): ~we~\\nğŸ´ó §ó ¢ó ¥ó ®ó §ó ¿/ğŸ‡ºğŸ‡¸ second person, plural (2p): ~you/y'all~\\nğŸ´ó §ó ¢ó ¥ó ®ó §ó ¿ third person, plural (3p): ~they~\\n\\nHere are the German subject pronouns arranged by person-number combination.\\n\\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª 1s: ~ich~\\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª 2s: ~du~ or ~Sie~\\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª 3s: ~er~ (masc.)/~sie~ (fem.)/~es~ (neut.)\\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª 1p: ~wir~\\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª 2p: ~ihr~ or ~Sie~\\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª 3p: ~sie~\\n\\n\"Fem.\", \"masc.\", and \"neut.\" refer to feminine, masculine, and neuter subjects, respectively.\\n\\nNote the two options for 2s and 2p, (~du~ or ~Sie~) and (~ihr~ or ~Sie~). ~Du~ and ~ihr~ are considered informal and may express emotional closeness. ~Sie~, which is always capitalized, is considered polite and may express emotional distance. Importantly for Konjugieren users, ~Sie~ uses the 3p conjugations`Presentation of Conjugations`Treatises on German verbs, when presenting the conjugations for a particular conjugationgroup, use the following person-number order: 1s, 2s, 3s, 1p, 2p, 3p. Respecting tradition, ~Konjugieren~ does the same. For example, ~Konjugieren~ presents the %PrÃ¤sens Indikativ% conjugations of %werden% as follows:\\n\\nwerde, $wIrst$, $wIrD$, werden, $werdEt$, werden\\n\\nA conjugation has red letters representing irregularities in one or two of three scenarios.\\n\\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª First, there is a red letter if the vowel of the part of the Infinitiv, minus the -en ending, the ~Stamm~ (stem), has changed as a result of Ablaut, a phenomenon described in %A History of the German Verb System%.\\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª Second, there is a red letter if the ending on the conjugation differs from that of a regular verb like %machen%. The conjugation $wIrD$ demonstrates these first two scenarios because the expected conjugation would be ~werdt~.\\nğŸ‡©ğŸ‡ª Third, a conjugation is entirely red when both the Stamm and ending $ARe$ completely unpredictable. For example, the 1s %PrÃ¤sens Indikativ% conjugation of %sein% is $BIN$."
