            "state" : "translated",
            "value" : "~Voice~ (also called ~diathesis~) describes the relationship between a verb's subject and its action. Is the subject ~doing~ the action, or is it ~receiving~ the action?\n\nLike tense, voice is one component of many conjugationgroups. For example, PrÃ¤sens Aktiv Indikativ has PrÃ¤sens tense, Aktiv voice, and Indikativ mood.\n\nEnglish has two voices:\n\nğŸ´ó §ó ¢ó ¥ó ®ó §ó ¿ ~Active~: The subject performs the action. Example: \"The toddler ~ate~ all the cookies.\"\nğŸ´ó §ó ¢ó ¥ó ®ó §ó ¿ ~Passive~: The subject receives the action. Example: \"All the cookies ~were eaten~ by someone who was definitely in the other room the whole time.\"\n\nGerman has three voicesâ€”active and ~two~ distinct types of passive:`Aktiv`The subject performs the action, just like English active voice.\n\nExample: \"Die Kutsche ~fuhr~ vorbei, und eine TrÃ¤ne ~stand~ mir im Auge.\" = \"The carriage drove off; and my eyes filled with tears.\"\n\n~Goethe â€” The Sorrows of Young Werther (1774)~`Vorgangspassiv`Called the processual passive in English, the Vorgangspassiv is formed with ~werden~ + Perfektpartizip. This voice describes an action ~in progress~â€”something being done.\n\nExample: \"K. ~wurde~ telephonisch ~verstÃ¤ndigt~, daÃŸ am nÃ¤chsten Sonntag eine kleine Untersuchung stattfinden wÃ¼rde.\" = \"K. was informed by telephone that there would be a small hearing concerning his case the following Sunday.\"\n\n~Kafka â€” The Trial (1925)~`Zustandspassiv`Called the statal passive in English, the Zustandspassiv is conjugated with ~sein~ + Perfektpartizip. This voice describes the ~resulting state~ after an action is complete.\n\nExample: \"Sein Antlitz ~war~ von honigfarbenem Haar ~umringelt~.\" = \"His face was framed by honey-colored hair.\"\n\n~Mann â€” Death in Venice (1912)~`The Distinction English Lacks`The Vorgangspassiv/Zustandspassiv distinction doesn't exist in English, which uses \"is\" + past participle for both meanings. \"The door is closed\" could mean someone is actively closing it right now (Vorgangspassiv: \"Die TÃ¼r ~wird geschlossen~\") ~or~ that it's already in a closed state (Zustandspassiv: \"Die TÃ¼r ~ist geschlossen~\"). English relies on context; German makes it explicit.\n\nAnother example: \"Der Kuchen ~wird gegessen~.\" = \"The cake is being eaten.\" \"Der Kuchen ~ist gegessen~.\" = \"The cake has been eaten. Only crumbs remain as evidence.\""
